Comment: Ruckmen hit their peak in their 7th season, and we saw Gawn (111) and Grundy (122) stamp themselves as stars of the comp in theirs. English's 7th season was every bit as good. After a breakout 2022, English went to another level in 2023, averaging 119 and, more importantly, played every game of the season. Both Gawn and Grundy improved their average in the year following their first season averaging 110+ and we typically see greater consistency in the top ruck tier than the other positions. That's why it's historically proved beneficial to pay up in the ruck (#setandforget) as they often back it up. However, with Gawn, Grundy and Xerri all stepping into solo roles this season, it's a rare year that we have multiple appealing ruck options with significant price upside. I think I'd pass on English to start the season and hope he comes in cheaper when it comes to upgrade season, at the very least the jump from one of the other options will be far less.
Short: No reason why he won't lead the comp in scoring again, although lingering concussion issues and Gawndy freed means there might be better value in the ruck this year

Comment: For years, the Bont was far better in real life than he was in Fantasy. However, this all changed midway through 2020 when he went on a rampage to average 124 points in the second half of the season. He spent the majority of his time playing as an inside midfielder rather than splitting his time forward as he did earlier in his career. However, Bevo being Bevo, the Bont returned to the fwd/mid split. However, Dunkley leaving opened up a full-time midfield role for Bont in 2023, and he did not disappoint. A 117 average meant that he was the number one mid in Fantasy. It was his tackle numbers (7.5 per game) that were the surprise, and he looked a man amongst boys at times. At 28, he's in his peak and will continue to be one of the best players in the comp, in real life and in Fantasy. No winning team has started with a player priced over 116 since 2018, so while he could average the 123 he did post-bye in 2020 and 2023, I'll back the history and target a cheaper player with better upside as my M1.
Short: Rare the number one player IRL is the number one mid in Fantasy which was the case last year, however it's rarer for the number one mid to go back-to-back

Comment: We got the solo Marshall we wished for in 2023 and didn't he deliver - a 117 average, including 123 post-bye. He is a genuine stat-stuffer, with his ability to fill all stat categories. There was always the threat of Marshall resting or the Saints playing a second ruck, however neither eventuated, with Marshall playing all 23 games as solo. Jack Hayes is healthy this season and I think he will provide Marshall with a bit of a chop out this season, which is why I have him regressing slightly from his post-bye average. But we'll still see Marshall continue to be an elite Fantasy player and a likely top two ruck and out of the five is discussions (English, Marshall, Gawn, Grundy and Xerri), he's the only one without either an interrupted pre-season or an early bye.
Short: Genuine stat stuffer and if he keeps the solo role, he can continue the 120+ average he did post-bye

Comment: Oliver was the premier midfielder in Fantasy in the first half of 2023 until he injured his hamstring in Round 11. He didn't dip below 100 in that time, including the game he injured his hammy and some heavy attention from taggers. He returned from injured to play three games, a 126, 66 and 101, and then averaged 123 in the finals. That 66 was due to the Finn Maginness tag, so removing that he would be the number one mid in Fantasy. His off-season has been much documented and while I think he'll bounce back and have a point to prove, paying that price-tag as a starting pick you need everything to go right.
Short: Only dipped under 100 once, but his much-documented off-season and early season bye makes him an upgrade target

Comment: After breaking out in his first season at the Crows, Dawson moved into the midfield in his second season and went to another level, averaging 113 from 70% CBAs. He looked a natural in there, doing everything from tackling, winning the clearance and bobbing up to take his marks. He's now lost his defender status but keeps his relevance, as he comes into 2024 as the 3rd most expensive midfielder. The Crows continue to recruit forwards and defenders, so Dawson is expected to keep his role in 2024 and put-up top eight numbers again. His scoring did dip at the end of the season when Matt Crouch was in there (105 L5), but I don't read much into that and I have him as a top three mid this season.
Short: Jumped 12 then 13 points in his last two seasons and doesn't look like slowing

Comment: Merrett's 113 average in 2023 made it seven 107+ seasons in his 10 years in the comp, making him one of the best Fantasy players of all time. After a dip in CBAs in 2022, Merrett was a full time inside mid in his first season under Scott, increasing to 82% to finish the season. While he's shown he can push the 120 mark consistently (6 times in 2023) and will likely go 110+ again, history suggests it's best to avoid the top priced mids and instead target someone with more price upside who you think can perform in line. An upgrade target for me.
Short: 7 x 107+ seasons in his 10 years in the comp

Comment: Gulden's 2023 breakout will go down as one of the best in AFL Fantasy. 83 to 112, an increase of 30 points per game. And he didn't do it in the conventional manner of bulk CBAs and high tackle numbers. Is that sustainable? Well he displayed the perfect mix of inside and outside which saw him score high and consistently in all situations, so I think it is. Given how damaging he was, you'd expect more attention to come his way in 2024. However, at just 21, he's only going to be better and a likely top eight mid for the next decade. In terms of starting squad, the high price and early bye puts a line through him for me. But he's someone who I think we're going to want to own at some point, despite now being a MID-only.
Short: Perfect inside/outside balance will make him a top Fantasy player for the next decade

Comment: Taranto finally got the full time mid role he and Fantasy coaches have been calling for, jumping to 77% in his first season at the Tigers, compared to an average of 49% in his prior three seasons at the Giants. We all knew he had the potential - in averaging 115 in 2021 for the 13 games with more than 50% CBAs - however given the typical low scoring Richmond system, his 125 average pre-bye still far exceeded my expectations. He came back to earth post-bye, averaging 93, which netted a 112 full-season average. The optimist says he could be underpriced if he replicates the 125. That same optimist could see a change in coach from one whose style wasn't conducive to high Fantasy scoring mean more points on offer for the Tigers. However, I think where he's priced (112) is about where's he's at and his kicking limitations restricting him from winning as much outside ball as he has in the past. 112 will still have him right in the mix for a top eight mid again, but not the value, nor the bye, that you want with your starting premiums.
Short: 125/93 pre/post-bye split means he could go either way, and a new coach adds even more uncertainty

Comment: After steadily improving in each of his three seasons, Green genuinely arrived in 2023. With Hopper and Taranto gone, Green went from 58% CBAs to 84% and boosted his average by 24 points. There were no concerns about his ball winning ability, however there was around his low kick-to-handball ratio and lack of marks and outside game. However, he squashed these concerns with four scores over 120, including a 170. Given his age and the way he finished the season (122 in his last 5), he's the most likely of the top eight mids to improve on his starting price in 2024. Add the Round 3 bye in the mix and I personally will be hunting for someone cheaper at M1. Something tells me the 23-year-old has a few more levels to go though, and Roos and WC first up makes the case to start him then offload on his bye.
Short: A natural ball winner now playing the right role and at 23, he's only getting better

Comment: After a super 2022, which including an All-Australian and winning the AFLPA's MVP, Brayshaw had a 'down' year in 2023. He was rumoured to have been dealing with a knee issue and regressed behind Serong as Freo's best mid, but he still managed to average 110. This was due to his elite mix of tackling in the inside and then bobbing up for marks on the outside, the perfect inside/outside game for Fantasy. My personal opinion is he needs to work more on his inside game (33% contested rate compared to 45% for the top eight mids, four clearances compared to 6) and less on the cheap marks. As a Fantasy coach I can't complain and with Serong now the tag threat, he should continue to be a 110+ mid. 27 Feb Update: With Fyfe looking great inside and Young still staying there, could we see a slight dent into Brayshaw's CBAs? It might only be to 70%, but at that top price, I think I'd want to be sure it will remain the 80% he finished 2023 with.
Short: Back-to-back 110 seasons, despite having a down year and a knee issue

Comment: Laird entered 2023 as the clear number one man in Fantasy, following a massive 120 average in 2022. However, he proved a poor starting selection in 2023, despite still averaging 109, which shows you need a lot to go right when paying up for premiums in Fantasy. Laird feasted in 2022 when he was the main man in the middle, alongside fellow inside bulls of Ben Keays, Matt Crouch, Sam Berry, Harry Schoenberg and Rory Sloane. The Crows played a very contested game-style and the tackling and clearance machine feasted. There was a clear shift in style and personnel to start 2023, with the more direct Jordan Dawson moving in and stints from Josh Rachele and Jake Soligo. Laird got left behind at times and averaged 107 pre-bye. However, they went back to their old crew to finish the year and Laird went back to the 114 average. I personally believe the Crows should continue to get speed in there, but if they continue with Crouch as their M3 in 2024, we should see Laird continuing on his 114 ways.
Short: Has averaged 114 since moving in the middle in 2020, but the introduction of Dawson in 2023 and more speed might stop him from going higher

Comment: We haven't seen a Fantasy prodigy like him. Excluding the Finn game which finished his H&A season, he averaged 112, starting as a running half-back and finishing as a midfielder. The tag threat will always be there, but I have him improving again to be the clear D1 for 2024. With the early bye and Finn lined up for Round 4, he's an upgrade target for me after his bye. But it's almost a matter of D1 by how much, so he doesn't have to outperform his price as much as other positions to prove a worthy selection.
Short: The clear D1 for 2024 and every chance to be the M1 of 2025

Comment: After being a tease in Fantasy ever since he averaged 83 in his debut year, Serong broke out in 2023 to be a top-line midfielder IRL and Fantasy. It's no question midfielders rely on CBAs for scoring and Serong hit the 80%+ mark in both CBAs and TOG, the combo we see with the top Fantasy mids. With the role upside exhausted, he'll need to rely on natural development to improve again, something that should happen given he's still just 23. His outside game (3.3 marks per game v top eight mids of 4.3) is an area of improvement that should come with another pre-season under his belt. However, I doubt it will be enough to see him prove to be a great starting selection given his price and the added attention that will likely come his way. 27 Feb Update: With a bit more depth in Freo's midfield, I'm more confident in Serong than Brayshaw now.
Short: Arrived in 2023 with a boost in CBAs and TOG, hard to see him improving much more unless he adds more of an outside game

Comment: Parish has the attributes to be a top-line Fantasy asset. He is a genuine ball magnet and with all the attention going to Merrett, he's never in danger of a tag. He averages almost two tackles less than the top eight mids, and he needs to get this to over five per game to become a 110 averaging top eight mid. I think he can do that, and I think he has the five point upside needed from this high price point needed to be a decent starting pick. I'm expecting big things in 2024.
Short: Ball magnet who avoids the tag, that's what I like from my Fantasy mids

Comment: We probably talk about CBAs too much in Fantasy circles, however Petracca's history shows why we are always chasing that magic 80% mark. After a dominant 2021, which saw him finish as a top eight midfielder, he's been used as a MID/FWD, dropping his CBAs from 79% in 2021 to 62% in 2023 (56% post-bye). With Melbourne's forward woes, there is always a chance this split will continue. If it doesn't however, we could see a Bontempelli-like 'breakout' in 2024 given he still managed 106 despite the role and Melbourne's midfield is looking rather thin. Worth a watch.
Short: Managed 106 despite the forward split, could be a top-liner if full time mid but that's no guarantee with Melbourne's forward woes

Comment: The breakouts of 2023 continued, with Rozee bumping his average 15 on the back of his first season as a full-time mid. His 113-post-bye is eye catching, in a time where Butters was getting most of the attention. He certainly has Fantasy IQ to him, running hard for cheap plus-6ers, which we love. He'll continue to be a top-line Fantasy asset, despite losing his forward status.
Short: 113 post-bye means he will remain relevant in 2023 despite being MID-only

Comment: No doubting Treloar has been a Fantasy stud over the journey, and showed he still has it by averaging 107 post-bye and 117 in L5 of 2023. However, he's been restricted by soft tissue injuries for a number of years now and at 31 and in a stacked midfield, it's not something I want to take a risk on.
Short: 31 with soft tissue issues, pass for me despite his Fantasy history and 115 L5 average

Comment: Sicily is a genuine one of a kind in Fantasy. His ability to find space and accumulate marks and kicks as a key position defender is remarkable. If I had to pick one player to get the highest score in a quarter, I'd probably pick Sicily. The issue is he doesn't just get cheap possessions, his intercept and kicking ability is as good as there is, making him a vital cog in the Hawks system. Due to this, we saw him get attention from multiple teams throughout the season, why wouldn't you tag him if you were an opposition coach? That's the only thing holding him back from being a Fantasy stud, making him a high risk/reward pick. 18 Feb Update: James Blanck will miss the season with an ACL. Sicily averaged 114 with Blanck in 2023 and 91 without. It's limited data but certainly shows that Sicily has to play more lock-down/key when Blanck is out of the side. I've bumped him down but ever so slightly as I think Hawks know it's best for their team for Sicily to play the third tall and they will replace Blanck with another lockdown. 23 Feb Update: DGB has also gone down now. I've had to bump Sicily slightly again.
Short: Opposition attention and Hawks being more competitive could hold him back from being a Fantasy stud, making him a high risk/reward pick

Comment: Typically, we want our players to get increases in CBAs. However, when you have multiple 110+ seasons as a defender, including a career average of 117, then a move to the midfield may not be a good thing. Docherty averaged a career high 22% CBAs in 2023, which increased as Blues went on their winning streak in the second half of the season. He's lost his defender status as a result, and a 104 average as a MID-only will leave him well short of the top 8. However, we know what he's capable of as a defender, so while I don't think he's worth starting with, he's certainly worth monitoring to see if he returns to his Fantasy-friendly role in defence.
Short: Will need to move back into defence to get back to being a top-line Fantasy asset

Comment: In a year where so many players broke out after finally getting the midfield roles we've been craving, Dunkley's 2023 from a Fantasy perspective was a little disappointing. We all knew Dunkley could score as well as any player in Fantasy. He averaged 118 in the last five games of 2018, 127 in the last half of 2019 and 116 in the first half of 2021. However, he just never put together a full season, largely due to Bevo taking him out of the midfield. He managed to match his career high of 110 in 2022 from just 51% CBAs, which is the clearly the lowest of any player with a 110 average. The move to the Lions was meant to bring 80% CBAs and 110+ scoring. The CBAs were there, however the scoring was not, averaging 104 for the season. It was evident the Bulldogs system was far more conducive to high Fantasy points, but he also appeared to play a more defensive role in the midfield. He also had a calf issue that hampered him at times. He's lost his forward status which has always been his big appeal, but I have a feeling he returns to a 110+ average in his second season in the Lions' system.
Short: Didn't deliver the big scoring expected of him, but the role was there and I think it will come in 2024

Comment: Crouch has quietly put together a very impressive Fantasy career. He backed up his 2022 season where he finished as a top eight midfielder with a 103 in 2023, highlighted by 107 post-bye. He was a point-per-minute stud at his time in Adelaide, going at 142 and 137 points per 100% game time in 2017 and 2019. I had him dropping out of the Saints' midfield as he, Ross and Steele are a little 'one-paced', however apparently he's a favourite of Lyons and I think it will be Ross who pushes out. That should see Crouch maintain his 70%+ CBA role in 2024. That should see him continue to be a decent Fantasy scorer, however at 30, it's hard to see him improving enough to challenge the top eight in 2024.
Short: He's a favourite of Lyons and likely to maintain his 70%+ CBA role, but at 30 it's hard to see much improvement in him, especially with these young kids coming

Comment: The much-loved Bulldog has been a star mid for the majority of his career, so it's crazy to think that it took until his 13th season to average over 100 for the first time. He’s your classic inside mid, meaning they have a lot more impact in real life than their Fantasy scores suggests. However, he was the real winner from the Dunkley trade and was the preferred midfielder over Smith and Macrae. Excluding his concussion game, he averaged 107 which is knocking on the door of the top 8. I think his role is safe, which is a big call for a midfielder coached by Bevo, but even with that role he's going to be a level below the top tier mids given his below average kick and mark numbers.
Short: A gun inside mid in real life, but one season above 100 once in 13 seasons shows his Fantasy game is limited

Comment: Nank has been a consistent ruck since arriving at the Tigers, averaging between 80 and 90 in five of the past six seasons, but put up career best numbers in 2023 to average 102. That ranked him 3rd amongst rucks, even with less CBAs than the other top rucks. He's still under 30 and with the Tigers trading Soldo, he could replicate those numbers in 2024. However, he's not going to be a top two ruck, nor will improve 10 points, so he's not a great starting option.
Short: Career best numbers in 2023, age and no Soldo means he could match that again, but I doubt he'll be a top four ruck with Gawndy released

Comment: Sinclair proved his 8th year breakout in 2022 was no fluke, putting up a 102 average. He features the dream combo of CBAs and KIs, so he's always involved in the play. The CBAs reduced as in the second half of the season when Jack Steele returned, and he scored more freely, averaging 108 post-bye and 112 in the L5. The top three defenders are pretty secure, and he is part of that. I feel like he's going to be closer to 110 than 100, which would make him a viable starting selection as a premium defender. 23 Feb Update: Pre-season calf injury will see him miss the practice matches and be touch and go for Round 1. That's enough to scare me away as a starting pick.
Short: A lock for a top three defender, and based on his form when Steele returned (108 post-bye, 110 L5), he could be better than that

Comment: Leon out meant Cogs got the mid-time he and Fantasy coaches were craving, averaging 79% CBAs after being under 50% the prior two seasons. He went on to have a solid season, averaging 102, but didn't have the huge uptick that we saw from the other 'forwards' of Taranto, Gulden, Butters and Rozee. He has a nice Fantasy game to him where he spreads for marks and high tackle numbers, but these two metrics were down in 2023 compared to his two 111 seasons of the past. While his role is favourable, he's now playing second fiddle to Tom Green and Josh Kelly, so I think scores around the 100 mark will be the limit of the now 30-year-old. That's not enough to consider now that he's lost his forward status.
Short: Back in the middle but not the 110+ Cogs of the past with Green & Kelly taking control

Comment: While Anderson continued to improve his Fantasy output (74 to 81 to 98 to 101) his 2023 season was a frustrating one. He got off to a horrific start, averaging 78 in his first three games and went completely missing in games. Certainly not what I expected of a 22-year-old, former top two pick in his 4th season. He then got going, averaging 127 in his next five to be the form player in Fantasy. Just when I thought my bullish pre-season opinion of him was justified, he averaged 85 in his next 3. The remained up and down all season, which is what you get from an inside midfielder who gets below average tackle numbers, almost three less per game than the top eight mids. I think he has the ability to become a 110-averaging midfielder, but I'll need to see a boost in tackle ability before being confident enough to jump on. Hardwick at the helm, whose system is not conducive to high Fantasy scoring, adds to the hesitation.
Short: Has the ability to become a 110-averaging midfielder, but I'll need to see a boost in tackle ability to limit his inconsistency

Comment: Viney is a pure inside midfielder and a gun in real life, but for the most part of his career, he didn't get enough easy ball to turn from a 90-100 guy to the 110+ required to be an elite Fantasy midfielder. It appeared to turn in the second half of 2023, averaging 113 post-bye. We've seen pure inside mids add to their game and suddenly find an extra 10 points per game, most famously Ollie Wines in his Brownlow year who put the writing on the wall with a 110+ second half average also. The bump came due to Oliver being out and it's very hard for a third option mid to average over 100, but if Oliver misses the start of 2024 we should see Viney eclipsing his modest career best average of 101
Short: Had a boost when Oliver was out (113 post-bye), and if Oliver misses the start of 2024 we should see Viney eclipsing his modest career best average of 101

Comment: It was apparent from early in his career that Butters was going to be a star of the comp one day. It's meant a lot of Fantasy coaches (none more than me) were burnt a few times backing him in for a breakout. However, that breakout came in 2023. He started slow following an AC injury in the pre-season, averaging 82 in his first seven games. From there he exploded, averaging 107 the rest of the way. He displayed a perfect blend of inside and outside and should only improve his tackle game as he gets stronger and spends more time in the middle. Like the other gun forwards of the 2023 season, he's lost his forward status. However, as a MID-only who is priced at 99 but averaged 107 when he got going, he's got the price and points upside to still be a viable pick this season.
Short: Averaged 107 when he got going last year and should only improve as he gets stronger and more experienced

Comment: After four seasons in a row averaging in the 80s, Ryan had a career best Fantasy season, averaging 99 for the year and making him the 4th most expensive defender heading into 2024. He led the comp in kicks per game and was 4th for marks. He can also go very big on his day, two scores over 150 in the past two seasons. However, Freo's slow ball movement and kick-mark nature was criticised, and I expect them to speed things up a bit in 2024, meaning less chances for easy plus-6ers for Ryan. While I still have him as a top 10 defender, he might have maxed out in 2023.
Short: Now a safe Fantasy defender with a high ceiling, but has been maxed out with Freo trying to move it quicker?

Comment: After looking like a future stud when he averaged 99 in his second season, Kelly finally returned to that mark in 2023. Considering how bad West Coast were, he had an incredible season. As good as he was in his second season (All-Australian) and last year (Best & Fairest), he still couldn't average over 100, largely due to his below average marks (3 per game) and tackles (5 per game). It's been a trend his career to date and I doubt we'll see him push to the 105+ average required to be a Fantasy-relevant midfielder.
Short: Great season but lack of marks and tackles still had him fall short of 100 and a pre-season hamstring injury doesn't help

Comment: After displaying flashes of Fantasy brilliance throughout his career, Newman exploded at the end of 2023 to average 109 post-bye and 124 L5, making him the 2nd best defender in that time. It certainly helped that Williams was out for the season and Docherty spent more time in the midfield, however he still had Saad being the main free runner back there and Newman was forced to play defensive matchups most weeks. This made his breakout season at age 30 even more impressive. It's hard to go against him based on what he produced, but with Williams returning and Docherty likely to spend more time down back, I think he'll score more in line with where he was pre-bye (89) rather than the 109 post.
Short: The second-best defender in the game to finish 2023, but Williams returning and Doch potentially down there, I can't see him replicating it

Comment: After averaging 110+ three seasons in a row (including 121 in 2021 with 134 post-bye), Steele was one of the more disappointing players in Fantasy in 2023. He certainly had excuses, breaking his collarbone after Round 2 and arguably returning too early, missing just three weeks. He scored under 90 in seven of his next 10. Adding to the AC joint, he also tweaked his MCL and continued to play and was also rumoured to have a sore Achillies. He looked more like the Steele of old to finish the season, averaging 125 from Round 17 to 20, but he finished the season with a 59, 67 and 91 in his last 4. There is no question his 2023 season (and 2024 price) was impacted by injury. The issue was more how he looked when healthy. The Saints are trying to inject speed into their play and Steele looked a step off the pace at times. I think the days of him being the number one Fantasy scorer in the comp are over, but with his high tackle rate, an injury free season should see him at least go at 107+ which would be enough for him to be a good starting pick.
Short: Plenty of excuses after 3x110+ seasons in a row, the game is a bit quicker now but if injury free should push back towards that 110 mark

Comment: With a new coach and Hopper & Taranto to the Tigers, Kelly spend more time in the midfield in 2023 and had a great season as a result. However, he didn't hit the CBA and scoring heights I expected of him, averaging 97 from 54% CBAs. That 97 included a 30 (yes, 30) when Finned and a game he injured his hamstring in the 3rd quarter. However, with Green's emergence, Coniglio's bounce back and the evergreen Cal Ward being the preferred as the inside mids at the backend of the season, Kelly was pushed to a wing, where he played well but the wing is not conducive to high Fantasy scoring. I still believe he can return to be a 110+ averaging mid if he gets 65%+ CBAs, which he did to average 110+ in 2018, 2019 and the second half of 2021, but I don't believe we will see 65%. Still worth monitoring in the pre-season.
Short: Pushed to a wing to finish 2023 and will need to move back inside for 65%+ to have the impact needed

Comment: LDU's Fantasy trajectory looks very linear - 53 in his debut season followed by 71, 82, 93 and then 97 in 2023. However, his 2023 was everything but linear. The former number four pick started with a bang, 108 and 123 in his first two matches. He was then a late withdrawal in Round 3, returning in Round 4 but was a shadow of the player in the early rounds, not reaching triple figures again until Round 17. It included missed seven games for injury. However, after following a 63 first up from injury, he put up 121 in his next four and five 100+ scores in his six games. He then was a late withdrawal (again) in Round 23, and we didn't see him again. He's an emerging star of the comp and I think we'll see him go to another level again this season. The only thing that I see holding him back is the potential for opposition attention as he's clearly the Roos' best player. Priced at 97, he can easily surpass that by 10 points per game if he avoids the tag. However, there's a reason why these real-life explosive stars aren't always reliable Fantasy players and I think we'll see some downs amongst the ups for LDU in 2024.
Short: His best is more than good enough (121 from R17-R20), but given how damaging he is IRL, the tag threat will likely keep him in check

Comment: Noone saw Sheezel's debut season coming. The crafty 'forward' spent most of his time in defence and genuinely looked like Daicos in his first season, taking kick-ins and setting up play. He did have stints up forward and in the middle though, given the Roos were playing for development. He scored his best when he had the 'Daicos' role. In the 11 games over 100, he averaged 25% KI. The six below 90 it was 12%. With no Aaron Hall and Jack Ziebell, Sheezel should have the green light to be the main man back there this season and we could see a 'Daicos-like' second year breakout. However, the Roos are still in development and might want to see how he goes in the middle or forward, where he excelled as a junior. Worth monitoring over the pre-season to see if he remains down back, and if so jump on. 16 Feb Update: Spent time on HB in the intra, I'm taking note. 23 Feb Update: Had 42 touches (thanks @aflcentral1) in the first pre-season game, mainly across half back. It's the role not the numbers I'm reacting to, but he's now my preferred of the defenders priced 97+ as a starting pick.
Short: Daicos 2.0? Sounds like he'll be more mid/fwd which might cap his scoring, but if he returns to the half-back role look out

Comment: Considering he won a Brownlow, Neale had a very underwhelming Fantasy season. In fact, he averaged his least number of disposals since 2014 - including 2020 which had 16 minute quarters. He finished with an average of 95, making him the 31st best mid in Fantasy, only going over 120 three times (max 127) and failing to reach 90 on 10 occasions. He's a proven Fantasy scorer in the past, averaging 116 in the first half of 2022 and a league leading 120 in 2020. The issue with Neale is that he is clearly Brisbane's most damaging midfielder and teams quickly learnt that if they shut down Neale, they would shut down the Lions. The Lions know this and make a point to spread the load more in 2023, aided by the recruitment of Josh Dunkley. I imagine will see much the same in 2024.
Short: Despite the Brownlow, was the 31st ranked mid in Fantasy with Lions looking to spread the load more

Comment: We began to see the best of the former Pick 5 in 2023. The natural on-baller, who averaged 115 in NAB League, 10 more than ex-teammate Andrew Brayshaw in the same team, scored over 130 three weeks in a row from Round 6 to Round 8. He went on to surpass 110 five more times in his next eight games, before injury struck and he missed four of the final six matches. As much as I think he has a great Fantasy game in him, playing as the 4th mid behind Cripps, Walsh and Hewett, means there will be some low games in there, highlighted by the 11 games under 90. I think it will happen one day, but I doubt that it will be while Cripps and Hewett are still around as the inside bulls.
Short: A hat-trick of 130s shows he has what it takes, but 4th in line at the Blues makes it hard to be consistently over 100

Comment: Duggan had a career best Fantasy season, averaging 96. He had a nice combo of CBAs and KI, joining the likes of Jordan Dawson, Nick Daicos and Harry Sheezel - all Fantasy gems. I doubt he'll be required in the midfield as much in 2023 following the recruits and the young guns emerging, which is a good thing for his Fantasy scoring as his best when playing in defence. Plus, WC primary distributor over the last decade is no longer there. However, I doubt West Coast will be as bad as they were last year, meaning there won't be as much ball back there. So while he comes in as the 7th most expensive defender, I don't think he'll have the consistency to push into the top six in 2024.
Short: Career best 2023 but I expect less to fall on his shoulders in 2024, despite being captain and Hurn retiring

Comment: Stewart had been on the verge of the top six defenders for multiple seasons, however it never seems to eventuate, and he's yet to average 100 in a full season. It was an early concussion in 2022 that held him back and a knee injury on 14 in Round 1 last season. While he always appears underpriced and a top six candidate, he always seems to let us down. It's hard to predict Stewarts' prospects for 2024, given the fact he gets a lot of opposition attention (not ideal for a Fantasy defender) and that he's now over 30 in a team who notoriously rests their older players. However, on the other hand you can get a player capable of a 105+ average in your defence priced at 96. Update: talk of midfield, which is a shock, but then again he attended 15% CBAs in the L5 of 2023. The way he gets fed in defence and how many intercepts he gets (8.5 per game), I actually think he'll be better in defence, but it's something to watch in the pre-season.
Short: Still yet to average 100, despite being a top few defender for stretches

Comment: After a league leading 122 in 2021, Miller has had back-to-back regression seasons and bottomed out in 2023 to average 96. It started with hamstring tightness in the pre-season and then tore his meniscus in Round 6, seeing him miss the next 10 weeks. On return, he played a less prominent role, averaging 59% CBAs compared to the 80% he averaged in the prior two seasons. It appeared the Suns were looking at the future and the likes of Sam Flanders and Humphrey getting a run in the middle. It was probably the right call given Miller is now 28 and unlikely to be in their starting midfield when they push for a premiership. With a new coach, it's hard to know what role Miller will play in 2024. If he got back to a 75%+ CBA mid, he's the perfect underpriced premium that we can build our starting squad with. If not, he might struggle in a new system that will likely yield less Fantasy points, especially with Flanders, Anderson and Rowell all getting more of the ball. With a Round 3 bye, it might pay to use the first two rounds to assess the role before jumping on in Round 4.
Short: Pushed out of the midfield on return from injury, can certainly bounce back if Hardwick has him in his midfield sights but that's not guaranteed

Comment: Darcy managed a career best Fantasy season in 2023, despite sharing the load with Luke Jackson. However, it still involved an injury, which has been the constant throughout his career. I still think it's crazy that he's younger than Tim English and given he's heading into his age 25 season, he should be at his peak as English was last year. However, the top two rucks of the past have largely been solo rucks who take more than 80% of the contests. With Jackson there, that's unlikely to happen. And surprise, he's had another interrupted pre-season, so we might see another slow start. Despite this, I still think we could see him average over 95 for the first time, but there's not the upside as there is with some of the other solo rucks (Gawn & Grundy).
Short: Primed at 25, unfortunately for him he's not the solo ruck and he's had another interrupted pre-season, otherwise he could challenge the top 2

Comment: I've always been bullish on Will Day's prospects, but even I didn't believe the experiment of the skinny, injury prone defender as in inside mid would work. And boy was I wrong. Day excelled in his first season as a midfielder, improving his average by 35 points per game and winning the Hawks' B&F. More impressively, he was more impactful IRL than his Fantasy scores suggested. He displayed a great balance of inside ball winning ability and tackles with outside run and marks. He will no doubt improve again with another pre-season under his belt. I doubt it will be by enough to be a boom starting squad selection now he's lost his defender status, but I think he'll average over 100 in 2024. Update: pre-season foot injury might see him miss the start of the season. Bumped him down a bit. 23 Feb: Sounds like he's going to miss at least the first three rounds.
Short: What a breakout as an inside mid and going to be a star of the future, pre-season foot injury will slow his start
AA season on the wing, but only averaged 90 which shows how hard it is to score as a mid without CBAs

Comment: Whitfield finally returned to defence under Kingsley and finally looked himself again. He took a while to warm up, but averaged 101 post-bye and 104 L5. It shouldn't be a surprise, given he's averaged 107 twice before. He did have a mortgage on the distribution back then, whereas now he's competing with Himmelberg, Ash and Cumming. But at 29, I can see him remaining at the post-bye level of 101. That would be enough to make him a top six defender and underpriced at 95. If it weren't for the early bye, I'd be ready to be burnt again.
Short: 101 post-bye now back in his natural position and that would be enough to see him return to the top six defenders

Comment: After bursting onto the scene and looking like a top-level Fantasy mid for the future decade, averaging 92, 97 and 109 in his first three seasons, Walsh has been underwhelming in the last two. There have been a few factors for the regression. A pre-season syndesmosis injury in 20222 and off-season back surgery in 2023. The worrying part was that it was his back-half of 2023, when he should've been at full fitness and peaking in CBAs at 59%, yet only averaged 79. He won enough of the ball (averaged 28.5 disposals, more than the top eight mids), he just had a low kick-to-handball ratio (0.76 v 1.2 of the top 8) and lacked counting stats of marks and tackles. However, this turned in the finals where he increased his CBAs to 68%, the same level where he averaged 109 in 2021, and averaged 115, winning the Garry Ayres medal for the best player in the finals. Priced at 95, there is no question he's underpriced - he averaged more than that in his second season. A full pre-season for the first time in three years will do wonders. The question is if he can maintain the 105+ level which he needs to at that price. The early bye (Round 2) hurts, but it also means we can see if he maintains the 65%+ CBA number that he did in the finals and then you can jump on with confidence in Round 3.
Short: Injury interrupted pre-seasons twice in a row has seen a regression, but if the finals were any indication, we're about to remember how good Walsh is in 2024

Comment: Of all the breakouts in 2023, Briggs was probably the most impressive. From a 3rd choice ruck at GWS to All-Australian calculations, an amazing rise from the 24-year-old. He averaged the 3rd most tackles amongst rucks (behind Nank and Marshall) and under three HOs less than the top 2. That means his scoring is sustainable, as we saw throughout 2023 when we (I) was waiting for him to come back to earth. At 24, he's only going to improve. However, I doubt it will be by enough to contend with English, Marshall, Gawn or Grundy, so as he's the 5th most expensive ruck, I don't think he'll better that on averages in 2023.
Short: Skyrocketed to be a top five ruck and could stay there for the next five years

Comment: The mid-season draft sensation took his game to another level in 2023. He stepped up in the absence of Mitchell and O’Meara, but he actually didn't get the initial CBA bump I expected, going from 66% in 2022 with Titch and JOM in the side to 69% in pre-bye in 2023. This stepped up to 75% in the last five games, and his scoring reflected the boost, averaging 105 in that time. A 105 average at his price (93) would be a terrific starting squad pick. He has the tools to do so, and surprisingly averaged more marks than the average top eight mid in 2023. Where he lacked was tackles (4.3 v 5.9), which is a shock given he set the AFL record for tackles on debut with 14. One to watch in the pre-season, and Day out will only boost.
Short: 105 in L5 with the boost in CBAs, if he remains at 75% plus, he could go to another level again

Comment: Now this kid can seriously play. He improved his output again in 2023, however, his season felt a bit underwhelming. He followed up his 3rd season where he attended 79% CBAs in his last five to just 38% in his L5 of 2023. He's one of those players who are more damaging in real-life than in Fantasy, showcased by his 16 Brownlow votes last season, the only Swan to receive more than 10, after 12 votes in 2022. That's a lot of votes for someone who averaged 90 in that time. Heading into his 5th season, he'll no doubt improve again with fitness and natural progression. But with the Swans recruiting Taylor Adams and James Jordon for midfield roles, I'm not sure he'll get the role required for a 10-point improvement season, especially considering the opposition attention he receives, such is the damaging nature of his game. 27 Feb Update: Gets a slight bump with Parker out, he's now the Swans' number one man.
Short: Heading into his 5th season, the future AFL star should improve again, but he's one of those players who are better IRL than Fantasy

Comment: Houston has been a mainstay in Port's defence for a few years now. He's shown a high ceiling, scoring over 120 three times in 2023, including a 156, following five times over 120 in 2022, also including a 150. However, he's also shown inconsistency, going sub-90 12 times in 2023 (10 times in 2022). He did average 103 post-bye and 102 in finals, so he's certainly knocking on the door. I think I just need a bit more consistency.
Short: High ceiling but more consistency is needed to be a safe top six defender

Comment: Short was the number one defender in Fantasy up until in Round 7, 2022, averaging 107. He then moved into the midfield, and while CBAs normally mean more points in Fantasy, this wasn't the case, and his output has been down ever since. However, he didn't attend a CBA after his bye last year, and while his scoring wasn't eye-catching (note it included an injured 25), he began to be the primary distributor out of defence for the Tigers. A new coach means roles are uncertain, but with the early bye, I'm not sure you'd want to start Short anyway. He has an awkward bye in Round 6, so it's too late to wait to see what role he's in but too early to be bullish on him. I think he's just a watch for an upgrade target later in the season.
Short: Moved back to defence post-bye where he's been a top defender before, but new coach and early bye makes him hard to pick with confidence

Comment: Gawn has been on a steady Fantasy decline since averaging 124 in 2020, dropping 13 points in 2021, eight points in 2022 and a further 10 points in 2023. The last two seasons has largely been on the back of sharing the ruck duties, with Luke Jackson in 2022 and then unbelievably with Grundy last year. His CBAs reduced from 93% in 2020 to 46%(!) pre-bye in 2023. Not surprisingly, the Gawn/Grundy combo didn't work, and the Dees left Grundy out of the side for much of the second half of the season and all of finals. Again, not surprisingly, we say Gawn returned to be one of the best rucks in the comp, IRL and Fantasy. His season high of 162 came from 91% CBAs. In his three games over 120, he averaged 93% CBAs. In his 12 scores under 90, he averaged 57% CBAs. Grundy is now gone, and Max is back solo. At 32, we won't see him hit the heights of 2020, or possibly even 2021. However, lower estimates have him averaging over 100 which is enough at that price to prove a decent starting option. The early bye isn't ideal, but he does have until Round 6 for his first bye, and he's got too many points and cash to have to wait until then.
Short: His three scores over 120 last season he averaged 93% CBAs, no Grundy, bring it on

Comment: It's been a rocky ride for Rowell after bursting on the scene to average an adjusted 111 in his first four career games after averaging 124 at under 19 level. He's since battled injuries (shoulder, knee) and form, but finally showed his talent in 2023, leading the league in tackles, pressure acts and second in clearances. Unfortunately, this didn't result in decent Fantasy scoring. He plays completely inside with zero spread to get easy possession, highlighted by his 65% contested rate (top eight mids 46%) incredibly low 1.9 marks per game (top eight mids 4.3). He looked purely focused on his role which at times meant manning an opposition mid and winning the footy came second. This means his scoring is capped, only six scores over 100 and two over 120. Unless we see a distinct change in his ball hunting and spread, I think he'll remain around the 90-100 mark, which isn't enough to consider in Fantasy.
Short: Despite leading the comp in tackles, 1.9 marks per game is going to make it hard for him to put up any score of note
+23 points last season as the big bodied mid, but Essendon might need some more spark in there for 2024

Comment: Macrae was the most prolific Fantasy scorer from 2018 to 2021. However, you wouldn't think that after watching him in 2022 and 2023. Even in his good seasons, when he doesn't get the inside role he wants, he looks a shadow of himself. Unfortunately, it was this way for the majority of 2023 - just 36% CBAs after being a 75%+ guy for years. I expected Dunkley would open up an obvious spot in the midfield. However, the Dogs' preferred midfield mix was Libba, Bont and Treloar, with all three averaging over 78% CBAs. It's a very tight midfield rotation at the Dogs and there were multiple games Bevo even used Caleb Daniel inside over Macrae. From the outside, it appears that the Dogs wanted more pace in there and didn't want to sacrifice Bont or Libba, both of whom had terrific seasons. With forward status, his history and the fact he's not even 30, he has to be on your watchlist for 2024. However, I have the feeling we'll see much the same in terms of role for Macrae and we all know what that means. But in a weak forward pool, it will still be enough to be a top forward. Update: Smith out for the year should only help his cause. Although it sounds like Sanders has stepped right into an inside mid spot. I'll still need to see his role in the pre-season. Update: A pre-season hamstring injury is not ideal but my mind will still be made up if/when we see his role in the pre-season games.
Short: 36% CBAs in 2023 as Dogs wanted to inject pace in there, pre-season games will determine if the most prolific Fantasy scorer from 2018 to 2021 will bounce back or not

Comment: Of current players, Tom Mitchell has been the best Fantasy player of all. He was in his own league in 2017 and 2018, averaging 127 and 128 before missing the entire 2019 season with a broken leg. Since then, he hasn't reached those heights. You could put it down to the recovery, then being in a team that fast-track a rebuild and experimented with younger players through the midfield. A change of clubs gave me optimism that we might see the return of the Pig. However, I underestimated how 'team-first' they are at the Pies and Mitchell bought into that mentality. He averaged 93, three fewer than he did when pushed out of the midfield at the Hawks. He had a great finals series, but even there he averaged just over 100. There might be a slight bump in CBAs with Adams leaving, but I think the Pies will begin to give more opportunity to youngsters Nick Daicos, Finlay Macrae and McInnes. Sadly, I think the big scoring days are over.
Short: The former Fantasy stud is now a role player at the Pies and their 'team-first' mantra means his pig days are over
Brilliant season on the wing and 106 in L5 is about as good as you'll get from that position, but 13 under 90 shows how inconsistent the role and player can be

Comment: For the majority of his career, Mitch Duncan has been one of the few outside midfielders who are capable of scoring 110+ in Fantasy. He takes above average for marks and a high kick to handball ratio. The risk with Duncan is that he's now over 30 and had his share of soft tissue injuries in the past. We know Geelong aren't afraid to rest players, even if named. So you'll have nervous moments with him in 2024. For that reason, I’d prefer to start with safer options in defence, despite knowing he has the ability to be a top six defender.
Short: Over 30 and had his share of soft tissue injuries means I'm passing, despite his favourable Fantasy game

Comment: I might have a new favourite player in the comp. The former Pick 11, who was described as the best kick at St Kilda from the moment he was drafted, showed he was just that in 2023 in a breakout second season. He boosted his average from 63 to 91, which included averaging 98 in post-bye to challenge the top six defenders. The Saints try to get the ball in his hands at any opportunity, as they should. Natural improvement should see him improve again and he's going to be around the top six mark for the next 10 years. Whether he can boost his score to the 100+ average required to be a decent starting selection is the question, as his outside nature and lack of tackles typically makes it hard to sustain 100+ scoring, especially when there's another defender at the Saints going 100+. But he'll get close.
Short: A second-year breakout and 98 post-bye an indication of what we'll see for the next 10 years
Averaged 89-93 for all four quartiles of 2022 and 2023 (H1&H2 for both), shows the consistency but cap of the big Wittler

Comment: Dusty had a sneaky good season in 2023. The 32-year-old star hasn't been a Fantasy relevant player for six seasons now due to his lack of tackles (less than two per game) and averaged under 100 in that time. However, he managed to average 100 post-bye in 2023, including 105 in his last 5. With so many players losing forward status in 2024, he comes in as the second best forward and all of a sudden becomes relevant again. The fact he's now 32 and hasn't averaged over 90 in three seasons, it's hard to pay a price-tag of 90 knowing it's unlikely he'll improve it. So despite being in my starting 'Best 22', I don't think he makes a good starting selection.
Short: Back relevant with the lack of forwards but 32 and hasn't averaged over 90 in three seasons makes it hard to pick with confidence, said to be spending more time in the middle though

Comment: Daniel felt every bit of 'Bevo' in 2023, as he was used as a defender, mid and even forward across the season. Of all the positions, he does his best from a Fantasy point of view playing as a half-back (was a borderline top six defender from 2019-2020). However, the fact he comes into 2024 with MID/FWD status shows how little he was used there. Dale is now the main man back there and Ed Richards was used as his 2IC. That left Daniel in no-mans-land, and I have no idea how he will be used in 2024. With the lack of forward options, he has to be on the radar over the pre-season, given his career best average would rank him as the F1 for 2024. But that would require him to move back to defence and there's no certainty of that happening.
Short: The gun defender of the past comes in with MID/FWD status which tells you everything you need to know about Bevo

Comment: His 90 average doesn't reflect it, but Luke Parker had another very good season in 2023. He's as tough as any player in the AFL. Unfortunately, you don't get extra points for that in AFL Fantasy and he only managed a modest 90 points. He's had forward status in the past and following the recruitment of Taylor Adams and James Jordon, plus the fact he's now over 30, means we might see him spend more time out of the middle and possibly gain DPP during the season. Until then, he's unlikely to make an impact as a MID-only in Fantasy. 27 Feb Update: Set for a delayed start to the season after having surgery on a broken arm. With 78% CBAs in 2023, that's a lot of midfield opportunity available, the question is who steps up? Warner the big one for me, but Jordan, Adams and Shedrick the juicy ones for Fantasy. We'll get the rook in Round 0 and if any of those see more than 50% CBAs, I think we can start them.
Short: Will need forward status to be relevant in 2023, but there's a decent chance of that happening and a broken arm will see him miss a chunk of the season

Comment: The premier defender in Fantasy for 2019 and 2020, Lloyd has slowly reduced his scoring in the last few seasons. Once the Swans' primary distributor, he's now handed over those duties to Nick Blakey. He's still a consistent defender, and removing the injured 38 in 2023, he would have averaged 93. However, it's just hard to see him ever reaching the 100+ heights of the past and I'd rather target someone with more upside.
Short: Now seven seasons in a row of 90+, but at 30 he's becoming more of a role player

Comment: Came into 2023 discounted and despite averaging 90, he disappointed. In a football sense, he had the lowest contested possession rate of any mid with over 35% CBAs and also averaged just three tackles per game, compared to the top eight mids of 6.2. I personally think West Coast's inside brigade should be Tim Kelly, Yeo + the kids (Ginbey, Hewett, Reid) and see less of Sheed and Gaff on the inside. A foot injury in the pre-season might make that decision for them.
Short: A foot injury in the pre-season and new recruits will likely see him pushed out of the middle

Comment: Flanders is the type of player these stats are made for. After some buzz in the 2023 pre-season, the former Pick 11 was in and out of the side in the first half of the season, averaging 51 from just 8% CBAs. In that time he was dominating the VFL, averaging 139. He finally got his chance once Stewy Dew left, and averaged 105 post-bye from 38% CBAs, increasing to 112 in the L5 from 43%. He enters 2024 priced at 90 and with forward status, thanks to his first half of the season in the graveyard shift. The only flag is the new coach, so his role isn't confirmed, and the early bye (Round 3). It might be hard saying no if he goes 110+ in Round 0, but I think I'll stay strong and wait until after his bye.
Short: Got his chance in the back end and delivered, 112 from 43% CBAs in L5, if role sticks with new coach he can be F1

Comment: I had been waiting to see what McCluggage would produce Fantasy wise once moved inside from his customary wing role, given he played inside when he was in juniors and averaged more points than Tim Taranto. He made the move in 2022, however he didn't get the boost I was hoping for. He did get better as the year went on, averaging 98 post-bye. Priced at 89, there's certainly upside there. But he needs to average 105 to make him a great pick, and judging off his output career to date, that seems unlikely.
Short: 98 post-bye which is closer to where he's been the last three seasons, still a level below the top ones who have a stronger inside game

Comment: This time last year, we were debating who out of Young or Daicos will push into the top 6. After a few rounds, there was a clear answer. The former number seven pick didn't make the jump we expected of him, following his 90 average in 2022. Luke Ryan remained the primary distributor for Freo, despite Young's elite kicking skills. However, a move to the midfield at the end of the season was a turning point. Young averaged 58% CBAs in his L5, playing a defensive role as a big bodied mid. Freo have been crying out for a play of that nature and he passed all the eye tests to suggest he could be the man. He averaged 98 in this time, which as a defender and priced at 89, would make him a great selection. And you'd hope he can better that with a full pre-season training as a midfielder, which he is. I'm on board.
Short: A move to the middle late in the year where he averaged 98 in L5 is an indication of what’s to come

Comment: Greene has the potential to be a top six forward if unleashed, as he's shown in the past, he can be a prolific ball winner when playing in the midfield. However, he's one of the more dangerous forwards in the comp and as such has settled in that role. He can still push the 90-mark in such role, but unless we see an unlikely role change, there not enough upside to consider in Classic.
Short: Settled in the forward role where he impressively can push the 90 mark but not the 100s when he's played midfield in the past

Comment: After winning the Brownlow in 2022, and averaging 102 for the season (105 excluding his injured game), Cripps was knocking on the door of the premium mids. However, he returned to an 88 average in 2023, and unlike his underwhelming scoring seasons of 2021 and 2020, he wasn't hampered by injury. It appeared that Carlton made a switch to move the ball quicker, which led to less possessions for their mids. Cripps' impact was still as strong as ever, he just didn't have the high Fantasy scoring games that he did in 2022. It worked, with Carlton storming home and making a prelim. I imagine Carlton adopting a similar method in 2024 and that means Cripps will score more like his 2023 season, than his 2022. Therefore he's not the value that he appears to be based on his discount to career high average.
Short: Has been a gun premium in the past (2018 and his Brownlow winning 2022), but been a high-80s/low-90s guy for three of the last four and the Blues are starting to move it quicker

Comment: O'Brien still hasn't reached the heights of 2020 that saw him emerge as one of the league's best ruckmen. He averaged 123 in his last five games of that season and caught the eye of Fantasy coaches. Since then, he's regressed, which is rare for a ruckman of his age (still just 28). The Crows just don't rely on O'Brien as much and certainly don't use him around the ground as they once did. He'll likely be a high-80s/low-90s ruckman going forward so he'll be a handy Draft option, but there's not much value there in Classic.
Short: He'll likely be a high-80s ruckman again and even less if they hand over the reins to Thilthorpe and it will be even lower

Comment: Moore was introduced into the midfield rotation in 2022 and averaged 101 post-bye from 42% CBAs. He was brilliant there and there was hope that this would be a sign of things to come. However, he returned to his customary forward role in 2023, attending just 2% CBAs for the season. He scores great considering the role, averaging 88 for the season, the same as he was averaging in 2022 before the role change. With so many young mids rotating in the midfield at the Hawks, Moore is likely to stay as a forward for now. But he should always be on the radar as we know he can average 100+ if the CBAs come. 18 Feb Update: Ruled out for at least one month — including possibly Round 1 — after being diagnosed with glandular fever. Glandular can linger, so he's ruled out for me.
Short: Back to the forward-line after 101 from 42% CBAs post-byes in 2022, still can score but we'll need a role change for him to be a top six lock in 2024

Comment: After 11 seasons in a row averaging at least 98, Pendlebury has now gone sub-90 three years in a row, While still great IRL, he's finally slowing down from a Fantasy perspective. He still plays a prominent role in the Pies' midfield, attending 66% of their centre bounces. At 36, I'm waiting for him to step back and possibly get DPP at some stage during the season, but he keeps getting it done.
Short: 3 years in a row sub-90 shows he's finally slowing down
Outstanding season but wingmen are capped to the 90 mark in Fantasy, so this is the best he'll be

Comment: The mature aged recruit, who came into the AFL with some great numbers in the SANFL (109 average in 2018), showed a bit of a Fantasy game in 2023, boosting his average 17 points to 85. That included 90 post-bye and 96 in L5, so he's now someone we can't discount. However, he still gets the important match-up each week and I rather my Fantasy defenders to be accumulators only.
Short: Great season IRL and Fantasy, displayed a Fantasy game but role is still too defensive for me to consider
Back-to-back Colemans, but the fact he's only averaged 80 in that time shows the game isn't suited to key forwards

Comment: De Goey burst into Fantasy relevance in 2021 when he was shifted into the midfield and averaged 110 for the second half of the season. McRae has played him as a pure mid the last two seasons, however he's never met those scoring heights consistently, averaging 85 in that time. It been a mixture of both the Pies' low possession game style and the focus for De Goey to get his possessions in a dangerous position forward of centre. It's working IRL, where he's a genuine star of the comp, so I doubt we'll see the 100+ De Goey again under McRae.
Short: Now a genuine midfielder, however McRae's low possession game plan and focus to get the ball forward of centre means he might not be that 100+ player again

Comment: After back-to-back 97+ seasons playing on a wing at Port, Amon averaged 77 for the Hawks in a similar role pre-bye in 2023. He's always shown a great ceiling, surpassing 120 10 times over the last three seasons. However, like all wingmen, he lacked the consistency and went sub 90 30 times. He played more in defence at the end of 2023, averaging an impressive 102 post-bye from 20% kick-ins and 121 in L5 from 30%. Unfortunately, he didn't play there enough to get defender status which I think would've made him an easy starting pick. It's also likely that the Hawks move the ball quicker with a more competitive side, meaning less marking opportunities for their defenders who took a huge number of marks last season. I never like picking players in the hope of DPP and there is a chance he goes back to a wing role in 2024, so I'm out.
Short: Scoring had always been capped due to wing role, but move to defence to finish 2023 with a big spike in scoring gives him a chance to surpass that

Comment: Bolton is a genuine star of the comp IRL. However, he's yet to match those Fantasy figures given the high impact nature of his game. A new coach might want him to spend more time in the middle in 2024, as he complements Taranto, Hopper and Prestia well as he adds a bit of spark, but that's purely speculative. An early bye rules him out regardless, but at least we'll know his role and scoring potential once the bye occurs.
Short: Star IRL, will we see more mid time for him to become a star Fantasy player?

Comment: Worpel bounced back after two poor seasons in a row. After averaging 97 in just his 2nd season and backing it up with another 97 in his 3rd, Worpel genuinely forgot how to football - averaging 79 in his 4th season and dropped another 27 to average just 52 in his 5th. With all the young mids at the Hawks (Ward, MacDonald, Newcombe, Day, Mackenzie, Nash, even more Moore), I thought we wouldn't see him much again. However, he managed 67% CBAs in 2023 to average a respectable 86. I personally think Ward (23%) and Mackenzie (20%) should get more opportunity for their development and it shouldn't come from Day, Nash or Newcomb. Regardless, his inside nature means his scoring is capped at the 90-mark anyway, and won't be Fantasy relevant this season.
Short: Nice bounce back but more opportunity should be given to the kids

Comment: Redman backed up his breakout 85 in 2022 with 86 in 2023. He's displayed a nice ceiling over that time, with 6 x 120+ scores. However, with Ridley and McGrath also taking distribution duties, Redman is also prone to a low score (26 sub-90 scores in the last two seasons). It's going to be hard for him to challenge the top six unless he becomes the clear number one man back there, which I doubt will happen.
Short: Back-to-back 85+ seasons but didn't come on as a top six prospect as I expected and Martin set to be the main distributor may hurt his output

Comment: Scott had a terrific season, averaging 86 for the season but came home with 102 post-bye and 105 in the L5. He played a pure wing-role and did it as well as any in the comp. He's now lost his defender status, but with the retirements of Ziebell and Hall, Sheezel moving into the middle and the interrupted pre-season of Fisher, we might see Scott roam across half-back and feast as he did at the backend of 2023. As with Amon, I don't like picking midfielders who don't get CBAs in the hope they get DPP, so I think he's one I'd wait on to see the role and scoring. But he can certainly outscore that price in the right environment. 10 Feb Update: Low-grade calf strain in the preseason.
Short: 102 post-bye, including 128 in R24, was the best scoring wing in that time and if he can get the half-back role he could do it more often
Brayshaw has retired due to concussion issues, we wish him all the best for life after footy!

Comment: Dale has been a revolution since his move to defence, clearly putting up his best three Fantasy seasons. He'd need to improve by at least 10 points per game again to be a worthy selection in Fantasy and given his season splits were all around the 90-mark and more than half of his games were sub-90 scores, I doubt he'll suddenly become a high-90s defender.
Short: Been reliable since his move to defence, however more than half of his games were sub-90 scores, so I doubt he'll suddenly become a high-90s / top six defender

Comment: The mature aged SSP of 2022 backed up his impressive debut season with one that had him in All-Australian discussions in 2023. He had a stretch from Round 10 to 15 where he averaged 113, bucking the trend of the low wing scores. He had eight scores over 100, again impressive for a wing, but was also prone to a low one with eight scores under 70, such is the nature of the position. However, an off-season switch to the half-back role, with the Bombers making it clear they want to get the ball in his hands and for him to be the major distributor down back. This is only good news for his Fantasy prospects and he might have an impact once he gets defender DPP, but as per Amon and Scott, I'd rather wait until they have the confirmed stats and pick CBA mids in my midfield. 23 Feb Update: How many times am I going to bump him up this pre-season? I'm warming to the selection.
Short: Had a hot patch in the middle of the year to show he can score and now said to be the distributor off half-back, a role that should yield more points than the wing

Comment: Zorko has been a Fantasy stalwart throughout his career. His scoring is boosted by above average kick-to-handball ratio, marks, goals and tackles. With all this combined, he's a unique player who doesn't require 30 touches to get a decent Fantasy score. However, he's now 34 and coming off a number of injuries in the last few years, so despite the thin forward-line and his strong scoring potential, you just couldn't go there.
Short: 4 games with less than 50% TOG in the last two seasons, has and can be a stud but the body lets him down too often now

Comment: Despite being very young in ruck terms, Jackson has the attributes to be a top-line Fantasy ruck. He came from Melbourne where his two scores over 100 came when he played more than 50% in the ruck. In his first season at Freo, he surpassed 100 six times, and averaged 64% in those 6, including a monster 149 when he had 88%. He also had six sub-70 games, and averaged 19% CBAs in those 6. Freo just signed Sean Darcy, who is also a very good ruck. In the 15 games with Darcy, Jackson averaged 77. He's got attributes that I think he can be a decent scorer even with Darcy in the team, but he's going to have to take the number one mantle for him to be the 95+ forward we're crying out for this season.
Short: Averaged 77 with Darcy and 99 without

Comment: Guthrie was a low-key gun Fantasy scorer in 2020 and 2021, averaging 105 across that time. He hasn't reached those heights since and battled with injury last season. Word is he's back to full fitness and while he's priced well below what he's capable of, he's now 31 playing for a team who notoriously rest their players, particularly those over 30. I can't trust that the minutes and matches are always going to be there, despite his discounted price. 23 Feb Update: Sad to see him hurt his groin in the first minute of the practice game after a strong pre-season. Will likely miss the first half of the season.
Short: Comes in discounted and his best is good enough, but we haven't seen that for a while and now that he's 31, I doubt we see it again - pre-season injury won't help the cause

Comment: Not many half-back flankers are taken as a top four pick, so Ash obviously has the talent. After an odd shift by Leon Cameron, where he played in the midfield, at times as a tagger, he finally moved back to his natural position under Kingsley. He had a very good season, but with Whitfield and Himmelberg also back there, there are a few mouths to feed for distribution. He'll be a top six defender in time, but I think 2024 will be too soon.
Short: He'll be a top six defender in time, but I think 2024 will be too soon

Comment: No easy way to put it, Mills had a shocker in 2023. After back-to-back 109+ seasons possessing the perfect marks/tackle combo we crave in Fantasy, nothing went right in 2023 and he dropped his average by a massive 25 points per game. It started with him forced to play a key defensive role after many of the Swans' key backs went down. His defensive attributes and versatility has always been a burden for him in Fantasy, often shifted to be loose man in defence or to a wing and play behind the ball. But never key defence. He averaged 12% CBAs from Round 4-6, including 0% in Round 5. He averaged 84 in this time. Swans then got some players back and Mills started building in the midfield, with 47% then 63% CBAs in Round 7 and 8, scoring 110 in the latter. He looked back to his 110+ ways. However, he popped a calf in the first minute of Round 9 when on 3, which was a tough break for those who traded in the underpriced mid. He returned in Round 15 when Swans beat WC by 171 and was subbed off just after half time. And to top it off, he injured himself on Mad Monday and will miss the start of the season.
Short: Nothing went right in 2024 and to top it off, he injured himself on Mad Monday and will miss the start of the season - stash for draft with potential defender status coming

Comment: 2023 was Cameron's first full season as the number one ruck and expectations were high after he averaged 93 to finish 2022 after Grundy got injured. He started pretty well, averaging 92 in his first 2, before injuring his MCL in Round 3 when on 52. He missed the next six weeks, before being eased back in, starting as the sub in Round 10 (64% TOG) and 75% TOG in Round 11. He then averaged 104 in his next 3, including a game rucking against the Gawn/Grundy combo and looked to be a top six forward candidate for the run home. However, Cameron missed a week for injury and Mason Cox started to take more of the centre-bounce ruck contests, and had a great impact. So much so that Cox was the Pie's number one ruck throughout the finals, leaving Cameron to attend 33% of the centre bounces during the finals. With McStay out for the season and Cox's influence late in the year, there's a chance we see Cameron spend more time forward in 2024 and now that he's lost his forward status, he doesn't present as a great starting option in Fantasy.
Short: Spent more time forward late in the season with Cox being the main man and we might see more of that in 2024 with McStay down
Terrible news with Smith out for the year with an ACL
The man can score (above 110 PP100% TOG the L5 seasons, 120 VFL avg '23) but Dunkley coming in massively hurt his spot in the side, couldn't get away from the sub vest and doubt that will change
Scores better than the average key forward, and averaged 96 pre-bye in 2023 which would make him a clear top 6, but it's too hard for a key forward to sustain that level for a full season

Comment: Once a high-scoring defender, Crisp has become a full-time midfielder since McRae arrived and his scoring has taken a hit as a result. He's well under-priced what's he's capable of, but as a midfield only option who has averaged sub-90 in the last 18 months, I can't have him.
Short: Averaged sub-90 since moving from defence, unless we see an unlikely role change, he's not going to be relevant in 2024
Shattering knee injury late 2023 and will miss most of 2024, showed enough to suggest he'll be a star in the future
Averaged around the 80-mark since being the number one ruck, that's a level below the top ones

Comment: The highly rated 24-year-old has had his fair share of injuries in the last few seasons. A beautiful kick and found his spot on a half-back flank and shown some great signs, including just one score under 89 in his last seven of 2023. It's this type of consistency that Powell hasn't had to date, but under Hardwick who was noted for having high scoring half-backs (Houli, Short), Powell should have a career season in 2024. The early bye (Round 3) rules out any chance of starting with him, but I'm quietly confident we'll see him push his average above 90 in 2024.
Short: Yet to have a full run of it, but showed flashes of brilliance (IRL and Fantasy), so if he can improve his consistency under Harwick, he could be a sneaky option
The Irishman was second to Newcombe for CBAs in 2023 and showed great improvement, but I doubt we'll see him improve to be a relevant MID-only option

Comment: After a prolific junior career and earning his stripes in defence once drafted, McGrath moved to the midfield in 2020. He looked good initially, but had back-to-back low-80 seasons and reducing CBAs as he mixed his time between midfield, wing and half-back. Brad Scott committed to settling McGrath on a half-back flank, however, it didn't result in much change to his scoring, with another low-80 season. There's too much competition for distribution at the Dons, with Redman, Ridley and Hind taking a lot of kicks and now add in Nic Martin, so unless something changes, I don’t think we’ll see McGrath breakout to be a top six defender.
Short: A move to defence for the former number one pick didn't result in any improvement in scoring and now has Martin to compete with
Been a solid 80s-guy since moving to defence, as have many of his defensive teammates and out of all of them, he's the least likely to push that to the mid-90s needed

Comment: Blicavs is such a unique player who has played pretty much every position on the ground. However, the upside isn't there unless he’s unleashed as a full-time ruck, which I doubt will happen.
Short: The mid/ruck combo shows how unique he is, but unless he becomes the Cats' number one ruck option, he won't score enough to be worthy

Comment: Smith has been a consistent defender for a number of years now without taking that next step and being a Fantasy relevant one. He always played second fiddle to Laird and then Dawson, but last year both played in the midfield, however he didn't manage to get a boost in scoring. His kick-ins are low for someone with such a nice kick (only 25%) and only reduced as the season went on. He's shown the 80-mark is his max.
Short: Had been behind Laird then Dawson for distribution, but with neither there in 2023, he didn't manage to boost his score enough
Undergoing his second knee recon

Comment: Matt Crouch has struggled with groin issues, a broken leg and form the last three seasons after being a 110+ mid previously. Despite putting up big numbers in the reserves, it appeared the Crows had moved on from Crouch. However, he returned to the team in Round 16 and played the rest of the season. He averaged 6.4 clearances a game and many thought he played career best football - as previously he's been criticised for being just an accumulator and getting cheap footy. Us Fantasy folk like cheap footy, and his 2.6 marks per game meant that he didn't average 100 in this time, despite having a big impact on games (averaged 108 SuperCoach points in that time). I was shocked to see he's still only 28, so there's no reason why the Crows should be moving past him if he continues to play the inside role, he did last year. I think his 110+ days are over now that he's playing a very team-first role to stay in the side, but priced at 81, a mid-90s average might be all he needs to be decent starting pick, lets see if he's in there in the pre-season games. 10 Feb Update: Sounds like he's a first choice midfielder, I've bumped him up a bit and getting pretty keen.
Short: Former stud got back in the team to finish 2023, his low K:H ratio and lack of marks means his glory Fantasy days are over but at that price he should smash IF he's in the team

Comment: Vlastuin had a career best Fantasy year in 2022 on the back of Houli retiring and Short moving into the midfield. However, Vlastuin gave up Richmond's primary distributor in 2023 as Short returned to defence and Rioli broke-out. Yze has flagged positional changes, but I doubt we see anything for Vlastuin to become a top six defender.
Short: Short returning to defence and Rioli breaking out saw Vlastuin drop back nine points after a career best 2022
Couldn't get back into the side after Round 7 and Young moving in the midfield will only make it harder, best on in the intra-club is promising signs though

Bounced back to match his career best 81 from 2021 to show he can be a low-80s defender, but word he's swinging forward which will hurt his scoring and give someone else (Sic/Amon??) 32% KI opportunities

Comment: Noble had been a regular in defence for the Pies after being picked up in the mid-season draft of 2019. However, he found himself out of the side to finish the season and at this price, you need someone with job security and more upside.
Short: Found himself out of the side after being a solid 70-80s defender

Comment: There was a bit of hope for Hopper leading into 2023, following a trade to the Tigers who lacked midfield depth. However, he wasn't great, averaging 81 points from 16 matches. He did have two injury impacted games and removing those he averaged 88, still well short of other midfielders with regular CBAs. However, he's had some consistent CBAs in the past, with 75% and 72% in 2020 and 2021 for averages of 88 and 90.
