He's the reason why you can't rely on pure inside midfielders for Fantasy, as they don't get enough easy possessions and marks (Hopper averaged less than three marks last season) to take their Fantasy game to the next level. Unless we see a bump in tackle or mark numbers, his scoring in Fantasy is always going to be capped.
Short: Yet to average over 92 in eight seasons, he has a capped Fantasy game with low tackle numbers for an inside mid

Comment: Ridley looked like an emerging top six defender after averaging 89 in 2020 then coming hot out of the blocks in 2021, averaging 108 in the first four games. However, his Fantasy highlights stopped there. The intercept defender, who was the Bombers’ main distributor at the time, now has to share the duties with Redman, McGrath and now Martin. He's got a great kick-mark game and displayed an ability to go large, twice over 120 and other of those cut short for injury. He had three games cut short for injury, so his average could've been closer to his career high 2020 season. He's still just 25 and I think there is upside in him, but while the Bombers have so many back there, I'm not prepared to commit.
Short: A nice kick-mark game with the potential to go big, but while the Bombers have so many back there, I'm not prepared to commit
Bounced back to average 80 again as he did in 2021 but I'm not sure he goes much higher with the other Hawk defenders taking so much ball
Evergreen forward scores above average for a key forward and for a 33-year-old, but not the ideal combo in this game, despite his high ceiling games

Comment: The move of Rioli to the half-back flank has been a revelation and he's fast becoming a star running defender of the comp. He even looked to be improving again on his 2022 season when he averaged 89 pre-bye. However, that regressed to 67 post-bye when Short returned from injury and to the backline. Yze has flagged positional changes, but I think there's no question he'll remain in the role, but with Short there also, he'll unlikely push that average to the 90+ mark needed to be a relevant defender this season.
Short: Was one of the better HBs in the comp to start 2023, but regressed when Short returned

Comment: Heeney has been the ultimate tease in AFL Fantasy. It feels like every year there is talk of 'more midfield time' for Heeney which never eventuates. In fact, he had his career high CBA season last year with 13%. It increased to 29% in the final where he played a defensive role of all things, but that didn't result in much to his score. With Adams and Jordon arriving, and the likely midfield boost for Warner, I doubt we'll see much change in 2024. He still manages to score pretty well for almost a pure forward, however there's no value in his price if he remains there. So unless we see that 50% CBA number in the pre-season and want to go down that road again. 23 Feb Update: Well I shouldn't be surprised as it's never easy knowing what Horse will do, but Heeney saw CBAs in the pre-season game. I'm not reacting too much, he's too good of a forward and they now have so many options to run through.
Short: The ultimate tease has almost run out of 'more midfield time' chances

Comment: Dangerfield has been on a steady decline since 2017 when he was the 2nd best player in Fantasy. He's now 33 and Geelong have always taken a cautious approach with their older players, indicated by his 18 games last season at just 65% TOG. That, combined with his MID-only status, makes him not an option this season, despite being priced 41 points below his career high.
Short: 3 sub-90 seasons in a row suggests the past Fantasy-stud is well past it in this game now

Comment: Moved into the midfield post-bye in 2022 and in 2023 led the Cats' CBAs for non-rucks. However, he's averaged just 80 in that time. His game is highlighted by his strong tackle pressure, but he doesn't hunt the ball enough and he's one of those who is too team orientated to make an impact in Fantasy.
Short: Pressure midfielder who is too team orientated to make an impact in Fantasy

Comment: The speedy half-back has now settled on a half-back flank at the Dogs and played constantly in 2023. However, he's second in line behind Dale for kick-ins and general distribution, which will cap his scoring below the 90 mark.
Short: Breakout season, but behind Dale for kick-ins and general distribution, which will cap his scoring below the 90 mark unless Bevo does something crazy with Dale as some training reports suggest

Comment: Rowbottom has always been highly rated at the Swans as a tough, high tackling inside mid. However, Swans have plenty of those and despite his high tackle count (7.3 per game), he could only manage 56% CBAs. He doesn't do much when he's not in the middle either, displayed by his extremely low marks, 1.1 per game. With two inside mids in Adams and Jordon arriving, I doubt we'll see Rowbottom hit the 75%+ CBAs figure he'd need to tackle his way to a 100 average.
Short: I doubt we'll see Rowbottom hit the 75%+ CBAs figure he'd need to tackle his way to a 100 average
We won't see him this season and we might not see him again

Comment: Hunter's 2020 average was always going to be a stretch, given it was a small sample size of 10 games of 16-minute quarters. But even ignoring 2020, Hunter was always a consistent 90-100 guy, finding space on his wing accumulating plenty of marks and kicks. So there was some hope a change of clubs could see him return to that form, however he averaged the exact same as he did in his last season at the Dogs. So I think he's now just a classic wing in Fantasy, who are MID-only, no CBAs and fail to go make much of an impact. A nagging calf injury has him in doubt for the opening round.
Short: A new team and played well, but still went sub-85 for the 3rd season in a row and back in-line with other wingmen

Comment: Sidebottom has been a Fantasy gun of the past, but now takes a much lesser role at the Pies, splitting his time between wing and half-forward and rarely seeing centre bounces (just 2% in 2023). As a MID-only in 2024, he's unlikely to make an impact if he remains in his outside role. Ignore the discount to career high, as his nine games in the shortened quarters of 2020 don't give an accurate reflection.
Short: Now a 33-year-old wingman and not in the role that once made him a Fantasy gun
Gun pressure forward who I imagine will be much the same for the Pies as he was for Freo

Comment: Witherden appeared he was going to be a Fantasy jet for years to come after averaging 89 in his first season in the comp. However, he struggled for opportunities, falling out of favour at the Lions and managing just 12 games in his first season at West Coast. However, he still showed he had the Fantasy upside, with five scores over 100 from those 12 games). He got a regular opportunity in 2023, however the scoring wasn't there, averaging just 17. He appeared to play more defensively and obviously West Coast liked what he did to continue to play him. He's always worth a watch as we know what he can do, but it appears the accumulating Witherden may be a thing of the past.
Short: Played all but one game in 2023 after being in and out the three prior, but didn't show the Fantasy upside he displayed early in his career, could see a rise with no Hurn, but is he Best 22?

Comment: Wines has had back-to-back disappointing seasons, dropping 37 points per game from his Brownlow winning 2021. He's battled with injury (a heart issue in 2022 and off-season knee surgery last season), but the main cause of his demise has been the emergence of the young stars Butters and Rozee. Add in Horne-Francis and there's been a clear shift to the new young mids at Port, with Wines' CBAs dropping to 42% post-bye (was 74% in his Brownlow year). It may appear that 2021 was an outlier, but even outside of that, Wines was always a 90s guy. He's still less than 30, so he shouldn't have fallen off a cliff as he has. Priced at 78, a 95 average is all he needs to be a decent starting pick, especially as he doesn't have an early bye. But to average 90+, he's going to need to get his CBAs back over 65%, which will rely on Willem Drew (also 50% in 2023) losing his role, and given he was just added to the leadership group, might be unlikely. A pre-season watch. 23 Feb Update: Hinkley is staying strong on the Wines full-time mid in 2024 and he's normally one we can trust. A mid-90s average is looking more likely by the day.
Short: No longer the main man with Butters and Rozee taking over but he's extremely cheap and not as old as his drop-off suggests

Comment: Salem has had a poor two seasons after being a consistent defender who always hovered just below the top 6. He's had excuses. In 2022 he injured his knee in the first minutes of Round 1 on 3, forcing him to miss the next 10 games. In 2023, Salem has been placed on a modified training program in the pre-season due to a thyroid concern. An uninterrupted pre-season could see a bounce back in 2024. However, even when he was fit in the last 24 months, he hasn't been the main distributor. Steven May takes a crazy amount of the kick-ins, and Salem took just 7% of them post-bye last year. Also the fact that he didn't go over 100 once, I don't think I could do it.
Short: 2 poor seasons in a row and has lost the distribution duties at the Dees

Comment: Keays has shown he can score in this game when in the right role. He averaged 108 in 2021 and backed it up with 106 in the first half of 2022, attending 80% of the centre bounces across that time. However, there was a clear role change mid-season and Keays has since spent more and more time forward, 55% in H2 2022, 34% in the L5 2022, 30% H1 2023, 20% H2 2023 and 6% L5. In his three games he scored over 100 in 2023, he averaged 49%, so there's no doubt he has the capability. The CBA trend isn't in his favour though, and with the Crows looking to inject some more speed in there, I think we'll see Keays spend maintain his forward role in 2024 and not be the top six forward who plays in the midfield that we're after.
Short: Steady decline in CBAs and scoring since mid-way through 2022 and now pretty well a permanent forward
The 32-year-old will likely take a back seat this season

Comment: Drew has become a regular in the Power midfield, playing 70 games in the last three seasons at over 50% CBAs. I feel like Wines will see more inside time this season and it will come from Drew's usage, however even if he stays in the prominent midfield role, he's a pure inside midfielder and lacks the spread and easy possessions to make him a relevant option in Fantasy.
Short: A regular in Port's midfield but plays a team-first role
Showed nice dash as a wing, but even the best wingers don't cut it in this game and Henry isn't that

Comment: Showed he was up to it last season, being one of West Coast's best as the number one ruck. He's always been spoken about as a future key forward and second ruck, and the off-season recruitment of Flynn means we'll likely see him step into this role in 2024 and cap his growth in Fantasy. 27 Feb Update: With Flynn set to miss the first 10-12 weeks, Williams will step back into number one ruck.
Short: Was the main man in 2023 and capped out at 77, will find it tougher this year alongside Flynn, but with Flynn out to start the season, he'll be WC's number one ruck
Had a career year in 2023 as a mature body in a young struggling team, it's hard to see him topping that effort

Comment: I've liked what I've seen from Hobbs in his first two seasons. He's slowly been introduced into the midfield, 15% CBAs in his debut season and 35% in 2023, increasing as the season goes on. He's got a hard-nosed style that I think will benefit the Bombers going forward. There is a bit of a logjam of mids at the Dons. He ranked 6th for CBAs last season, behind Parish, Merrett, Setterfield and Shiel. I think he'll leapfrog Shiel and Setterfield, and along with Caldwell, be one of the first choice mids in 2024. Unfortunately, he lost his forward status, despite spending a lot of time forward. He would've been a perfect punt if he was available as a forward, however he's too risky as a MID-only option. 10 Feb Update: Minor AC joint injury will see him on modified duties for a week or two, but nothing serious.
Short: Will hope to spend more time in the middle where he showed enough to suggest he'll be a player of the future
Fringe wingman who is MID-only, not a Fantasy option

Comment: 27 Feb Update: I like what I saw. Ryan is always going to limit the ceiling of Freo defenders, but he looked the main man in the match-sim and I can see him pushing his average into the 90s, which would make him a worthy selection.
Short: 88 in L5 when Young moved into the middle might be a sign of things to come

Comment: The man who has averaged 113+ twice in his career has significantly dropped in output the past three seasons. He battled with hamstring and knee issues in 2021 and a groin issue in 2022, which finally gave way with a complete rupture of his adductor in the final. This delayed his pre-season in 2023, however it was more the role change that hurt his scoring, dropping to just 39% CBAs and used as a pressure forward most of the season. This led to a trade request to the Swans for supposedly more midfield time. The Swans certainly aren't short midfielders, however they do love a tough inside mid and Adams is every bit of that. In a season with a lack of forward options, Adams is exactly what we're looking for - underpriced and potential for a bump in midfield time. The issue is the early bye in Round 5, but I'm prepared to start players with an early bye if they are value, which Adams is. We'll get a proper look at his role in Round 0, and I imagine most of the comp will be on board when they see him right amongst it then. 27 Feb Update: I had some doubts he will see enough time inside, but with Parker joining Mills on the sidelines, they're going to need his big body. He gets a bump from an already high base.
Short: In a season with a lack of forwards, a move to Sydney gives hope Adams can be one of the few 90+ options this season

Comment: Rivers has become a regular in the Dees defence since debuting in 2020 but it took until last season for him to display the potential Fantasy game that he showed in juniors. He increased his average by 24 points to 75, aided by Salem missing games at the start of the season and Brayshaw spending time in the middle at the end. With Harmes and Jordon gone and question marks over Oliver and Brayshaw, Rivers has spent his time in the midfield over the pre-season which is certainly interesting given his junior pedigree. We'll get a proper look in the opening round, but I've just bumped him up the draft order again.
Short: A junior stud who grew in confidence in 2023, rising up the Dees' pecking order for distribution and now we might see him move into the midfield
Nice bounce back, but still scores like a key forward
Back in favour in 2023 and played a nice role off half-back, but scoring reduced as Powell and Atkins were in the team and hard to see him improving on his pre-bye numbers

Comment: Injuries have limited Prestia from fulfilling his Fantasy potential, failing to play 10 games in 2020 and 2021 and playing less than 50% gametime three times in 2022 due to early game injury. However, he played his most games in 2023 since 2019 and didn't have any early injuries, however he averaged his least amount of points since his second season. The injuries might have caught up with him and he's not the player who averaged 100 in 2019. He's very cheap but he'll need a 100 average to make him a great pick, and I can't see that happening based on his low output last season.
Short: Had a cleaner run in 2023 but scoring took a hit, not a great sign and already some hamstring issues in 2024

Comment: Holmes has looked the goods in his first three seasons at AFL level, taking a prominent role on a wing and even spent some time inside. However, his scoring hasn't reflected his impact. Unless he becomes a full-time inside mid and adds some more accumulation to his game, I doubt he'll come into Fantasy relevance.
Short: A talented player IRL and introduced to CBAs in 2023, however his scoring game has been limited to date

Comment: There was a lot of buzz this time last year for the former Pick 3, and he had a good season without being the competition winning pick we were hoping for. He was used mainly on the wing as it looked as though the Giants were protecting his shoulders which he's had issues with in the past, however, was introduced more inside as the season when on. The scoring didn't follow suit and he likely tired playing his first full season. I'm excited to see what he will produce with another pre-season under his belt (his first two were impacted by his foot), and still bullish on his long-term prospects of being a top-end Fantasy asset, but I doubt we'll see the 20-25 point jump this season that he'll need to produce to be a good mid-pricer. 18 Feb Update: Sidelined for the Giants upcoming practice matches after suffering a shoulder injury in training, doesn't sound serious but not ideal.
Short: Future star and hopefully we see him more inside in 2024

Comment: It's hard to know what to make of Simpkin in Fantasy. After a breakout season in 2020 which saw him increase his average by 22 points per game, he improved again in 2021 by another seven points to 95 points per game and 105 post-bye. However, he stagnated in 2022, despite increased CBA minutes and then nothing went right in 2023 as he battled with multiple injuries and dropped his average by 20 points per game. A hand injury and two concussions saw him have three games with less than 50% game time, with a 7, 23 and 48. Removing those games he averaged 86, so still a level below his best, but it's hard to hit peak form if you miss regular games for injury. A lot of that might have also been due to how bad the Kangaroos were as scores are generally lower for losing teams. The rise of LDU also took some ball off him and with the depth of their midfield now, he spent some time forward. All of these factors are likely to continue, so I doubt he's going to become the 105+ mid I thought he would be early in his career, but a return to 95 will be enough for him to be a great pick at that price, especially if he gains forward status during the season. I'm on board for now, I just want to confirm his mid/forward split in the pre-season. 23 Feb Update: Not sure if they were just giving the kids a run in the pre-season, but lack of CBAs not encouraging. I now think there are better options in this price range.
Short: Was trending to be an elite Fantasy midfielder of the comp before stagnating in 2022 then nothing going right last year

Comment: After seven seasons in-and-out of the team(s), playing various roles including as a tall wing, Hinge settled in as an intercepting defender in 2023, playing a career high 22 games and averaging 76. He got better as the season went on, understandably as he got more confidence in his role, and averaged 91 post-bye. He'll continue in that role in 2024 and if he can bring the form he showed in the second half of the season, he's 15 points underpriced with the ability to score close enough to the 6th best defender. That would make him an okay starting selection and a very unique one at that. I'm not sure I could do it but if you're after a genuine POD in defence, Hinge could be your man.
Short: Breakout season in 2023, averaging 91 post-bye and in AA squad discussions, that level will see him be a top 20 defender despite being ranked 40th on 2023 average

Comment: Ellis has the Fantasy game that is capable of putting up some monster scores in the past. He had two scores over 125 in 2022, following his seven over 110 in 2021 (including a 169). However, as the Suns are becoming more competitive, there are less slow plays where Ellis is the beneficiary of some easy plus 6ers. He's also lost his defender status, which would be the thing to make him relevant.
Short: Always had a high ceiling due to his high-mark game-style, but now without defender status which removes any temptation
Scores okay for a small forward but limited in that role

Comment: It looked like the football world was at his feet when he entered the comp with an 89 average. From there, he's battled with injury and being in a struggling team - still yet to play finals in his 12 years in the AFL. I was bullish on him last year as he arrived at the Fantasy-friendly environment at Fremantle with a prominent role in their midfield following Mundy's retirement. However, he just looked old and slow, reducing his average to 75, despite being relatively injury free. It will likely be the Serong, Brayshaw and Young show in 2024 and JOM will be limited to a 'bit' role. If something were to happen to one of those three though, he does have the ability to push towards the 100 mark which would make him a knockout pick at that price.
Short: Yet to average over 100 in his 12 seasons, and not even a new environment helped that

Comment: The former top 10 pick has had a mixed Fantasy career. After a career high season in 2020 which included a seven week stretch averaging 121 with three 150s, McDonald's average dropped to just 68 points the season after and maintained that level ever since. After a stint on the wing, he's returned to defence but in more of a shut-down role. I know he's the co-captain, but he's far from the accumulator we saw a few years back. With all the injuries, he might even be forced to play tall in 2024. There is some chance he sees a lot of the ball, but I'll need to see it for a few weeks first.
Short: Has it in him to go big as we saw in the back end of 2020, been a role player since but with all the injuries and retirements, could see a bump in 2024

Comment: Former Pick 11 is now a regular at the Dons, playing 41 games in the past two seasons at an average of 75. I think he can play, he's just not in the first group of midfielders at the Dons, reducing his CBAs to 34% last season. That did result in him gaining forward status for 2024, and given how thin the forward-line is looking, it's someone like Caldwell who we need to be looking at. Parish and Merrett are the clear main two, but if he looks to leapfrog Setterfield and Hobbs (which I doubt) and be a 60%+ CBA player in the pre-season, he might be a smoky for 2024.
Short: Has talent and forward status keeps him relevant, he just needs to edge out Setterfield and Hobbs for that 3rd man in the Bombers midfield

Comment: Grundy has been on a steady decline - in real life and in Fantasy - since 2019 when he was the number one Fantasy player in the comp. He bottomed out last season after thinking it was a good idea to pair up with Max Gawn, seeing him spend a lot of time as a key forward and in the VFL. Common sense prevailed and he got out of there, landing at the Swans where he'll take the solo ruck role. He averaged 100 from Round 2 to Round 5 last season when Max went down, and 93 the year prior. That's a long way off his 120+ glory days of 2018 and 2019, but it's enough at that price to be a great starting pick with the hope the top two rucks get within reach. If it wasn't for the early bye then there would be no hesitation. Now with the R0 fixture you'll get an idea of how much cash he'll make before Round 5, and I think it will be too much to miss out on.
Short: Not many have a 49 point discount to their career high and while those days are over, he should bounce back to a premium ruck now he's solo again

Comment: The former top 10 pick was well on the radar this time last season following his finish to his debut season (89 post-bye) and the possibility of increased opportunity inside following the departures of Tom Mitchell and JOM. However, it didn't pan out, increasing his average by just three points per game and seeing less inside minutes (23% CBAs compared to 38% in his debut season). I certainly didn't expect Nash (69%), Worpel (67%) and Day (63%) to pick up that much of the slack. Of those, Day isn't going anywhere, winning the B&F and showing he's a future star of the comp. Nash came 3rd in the B&F and Mitchell loves him, so his role will likely remain. Newcombe (70%) came second. That leaves Worpel, and my view is that Hawks should move past him and give more minutes to the youngsters in Ward and Mackenzie. I'm not sure that will happen in 2024 though and starting Ward would be a genuine punt. The breakout will come at one point though, whether this year or next, so keep him on your radar. If Day misses the early rounds, we might see it come earlier.
Short: I wrongly picked a breakout last year following 89 post-bye in his debut season, second time lucky?

Comment: Atkins came back from the wilderness in 2023, playing the most games in a season since arriving at the Suns. He actually looked good, scoring over 100 three times in his trademark outside game which involves a lot of short kicks and marks. He was sub or subbed out on three occasions, meaning his average of 75 could have been higher, but that also reflects that he's not locked in the Best 22. At his price, he's certainly not worth the risk.
Short: Was back in the team after just 19 games in three seasons and when conditions suited, scored well, but will be on the fringe again in 2024
MID-only and behind in the pecking order at Geelong
Always been on my radar for more midfield time one day, but doesn't look like that will happen and scoring has been capped at mid-80s as a defender

Comment: Kennedy has a decent Fantasy game about him, however, has long been behind a number of players for midfield spots at the Blues. In 2022, he averaged 94 from 58% CBAs, including a season high of 122 from 76% CBAs when Carlton were missing their first choice mids. He didn't get over 100 once in 2023 and CBAs dropped to 34%. There were four sub-50% TOG games due to being sub, which resulted in his lowest average for three seasons. However, as a MID-only and not guaranteed enough inside time, I'm not buying into that discount.
Short: Not attractive as a MID-only option

Comment: Brad Hill has been disappointing since his move to the Saints, after once being a wingman who could average 90. I thought reuniting with Ross Lyon who was his coach during his career best footy was going to see a spike in scoring, but it didn't eventuate. He did have two scores over 110 though, and given the lack of forward depth this season, he'll remain on the radar if he can get back to high-80s, but I'm not holding on hope that will happen.
Short: Reuniting with Ross didn't result in his scores returning to the level under him at Freo
Returned from an ACL but at 34 the former captain is now purely a role player - currently dealing with an eye issue
Gun small forward, talk of mid-time this time last season, but as expected it never eventuated

Comment: The former top five draft pick has now averaged 70+ in four straight seasons, which isn't bad for a pure forward. It appears this will be his role going forward and I doubt a midfield move will come, which means he'll be too hard to trust in Fantasy. Can't pick unless we see Hardwick make a shock midfield move.
Short: A medium forward so unlikely to improve his average significantly, unless Hardwick changes up his role

Comment: After a sensational 2022 which saw him beat his previous career best average by over 20, Hewett reduced his average by 25 in his second season at the Blues. He had excuses, injuring his hand in Round 1 on 99 from just 70% game time and then struggled on return. He started as sub in Round 10 scoring 39 and then was subbed off in Round 11 with concussion on 25. He returned as a sub for two games, scoring 27 and 19, before finishing the season playing his typical inside role at the Blues, averaging 94 in the L5. He's pretty important to their structure and often takes the opposition's best mid, so I expect him to stay at over 65% CBAs in 2024 despite their star-studded midfield. He's proven to be capable of 90+ in this role, and priced at 74, a 90+ average would make him a decent mid-priced selection to start the season. However, the Round 2 bye throws a curveball and for that reason it's hard to consider him in your starting squad.
Short: A down year plagued by injuries following a terrific 2022, or was 2022 just an outlier?

A nice boost last year despite being a forward in a struggling side, which shows he had an above average Fantasy game for a key forward as he pushes up the ground for marks, but I'm not sure how much higher he could go

Comment: Saad has been outstanding for the Blues and is now an All-Australian half-back, indicating he's one of the top few defenders in the league. However, he's averaged 75 in the past four seasons, indicating he's far more damaging in real life than in Fantasy and I doubt he will ever be in contention to be a top 6.
Short: Far more damaging in real life than in Fantasy

Comment: Soldo has played backup to Nank for his entire career. However, a trade to Port in the off-season should see him become the number one ruck and hopefully see the TOG and CBA levels of other top rucks. He played three full games without Nank in 2023, attending 71%, 72% and 85% CBAs for a 107, 103 and 85. In 2022, he played once as solo ruck for a 72. He's shown he can average 90+ number one and at 27, he should be peaking as a ruck. I've got him taking a bit leap in 2023 and maybe in a year without a discounted Gawn, Grundy and Xerri and an early bye, he'd be right in the range for the R2 spot. Add to that, he's missed a big chunk of the pre-season due to a finger injury, so it's likely Sweet will take the number one mantle into the start of the season.
Short: A move to Port should see him take the number one mantle, where he's shown he can score, but a finger injury in the pre-season might open up the door for Sweet to start in that role

Comment: Hogan is a different type of key forward. When at his best, he works hard up and down the ground and can put up numbers that make him Fantasy relevant (his 89 in 2018 would rank him 5th amongst current forwards this season). He finished last season strong, averaging 84 in the L5, but even that wouldn't get him to the level needed to be a top six forward.
Short: Best season IRL since his early days, but a mid-70 average remained including a monster 188

Comment: Owens surprised everyone in 2023. The second-year player was in genuine rising star conversations in a field which saw two of the best rookies of all time. He did it in a different manner, playing as a medium sized forward, averaging just 15 disposals, but more than half of them contested with over a goal a game. He was used as an inside mid at times in his debut season and as a second ruck last year, which obviously aided his scoring. With Jack Hayes set to return, I doubt we'll see Owens in that second ruck role. So unless we see him back playing some inside mid again, it's hard to see him improving on last year. That is hard to say as typically players take a leap in their third season and Owens is better than your average third year player, but I think we can rule him out if he remains as a forward in the pre-season matches.
Short: Serious talent who does it in an unconventional way, might lose his second ruck minutes to Hayes so unless he turns into an inside mid, where he has been used before, it's hard to see improvement in year 3
Grundy's arrival has squashed any hope of Ladhams having a breakout season, despite showing a nice scoring ability in the VFL in the past (102 in 2022)

Comment: Berry was highly rated as a junior and showed signs early in his career, however, was often hampered by injury. He's had two injury free seasons, however he's been pushed to a wing and his scoring has taken a hit. Since post-bye 2022, he's averaged 6% CBAs. A MID-only with low CBAs isn't what we're chasing. Off-season shoulder surgery doesn't help either as he's had a limited pre-season.
Short: Plays purely on a wing now Dunkley is there which isn't what you want in this game

Comment: Looking back on my comments of past season guides, I've always had hope that Gresham will breakout. He teased us when introduced into the midfield in 2019, averaging 91 in the second half (100 in the last five), but managed just 14 games the next two seasons. He's since split his time between the middle and forward, but Ross Lyon wasn't a fan and played him as a forward, averaging just 22% CBAs post-bye and 7% in the L5. He scored pretty well considering, averaging 76 and 87 in those splits. He now finds himself at the Dons and their midfield is pretty one-paced. They've used Jake Stringer in there in the past to add some forward-half damage but he's past it now, and I think there's an opportunity for Gresham to see some time in there. We have seen Gresham in a consistent midfield role in 2022, however he underperformed from a scoring point of view, averaging 84 points from 60% CBAs. That might be his areas in 2024, which will leave him a bit below the top six forwards, but he'll still be on my radar given how thin the forwards are looking.
Short: A new team might see him spend more time in the middle where he's scored okay in the past

Versatile role player who has played almost everywhere, settled into a wing position the last few seasons which hasn't been great for scoring, sounds like he play HB in 2024 which should see improvement but not enough to consider

Comment: After two shocking seasons playing as a forward, JJ finally found his way back to the half-back role where he's averaged 95 and won a Norm Smith in the past. It didn't all go to plan though. A pre-season calf injury saw him start the season slow, getting just six touches in Round 1 and being dropped for Round 2. He returned to play a shutdown role on Charlie Cameron in Round 3 and that was his ticket back to defence. He averaged 87 in his next 6, with three scores over 90, and looked like he was back. However, a significant hamstring injury in Round 10 saw him miss nine weeks. He returned with an 84 but only played one more before an ankle injury finished his season. Hopefully Bevo has taken note and will keep him in his preferred role this this season. That could see him push the high-80 mark, which is over 10 points more than he's priced at. He's actually an okay option in that case, but I think they are safer ones in defence.
Short: Finally showed the signs of the player who averaged 95 in 2016 with Bevo putting him back where he belongs, and injury stopped him from a genuine bounce back

Comment: Big Goldy has been a great Fantasy ruck over the years. The Roos finally looked to the next generation post-bye last season, where he went from 84% CBAs pre-byes to 56% post. That saw him move to Essendon in the off-season, but even there, I doubt they will use the 35-year-old as their number one ruck.
Short: Now at the Dons, where I think he'll play a mentor role for Draper and Bryan

Comment: After a career best 2021 where he broke into the midfield at stages and looked great, Langford was always on the radar as someone who might break into the midfield full-time. However, he had a disappointing 2022, restricted to just nine games due to hamstring issues, and then used as a marking forward under Scott and to great effect. He kicked 51 goals and made the AA squad, a great effort on a struggling team. He's not going anywhere now after showing how damaging he can be, which means he's not going to be relevant in this game.
Short: Superb season kicking 51 goals and making the AA squad, unfortunately for Fantasy it means he'll remain in the deep forward role rather than the midfield role where he averaged 102 in the L5 of 2021
Showed a bit of a Fantasy game in his early year but been a valuable defensive forward in recent years, I doubt he's the one to see mid minutes with the departures but worth keeping a watch
Has been 68+ in three of last five seasons thanks to playing second ruck, but might see less ruck time with Soldo/Sweet arriving and even his 79 in H1 2023 wouldn't be enough
Been slowly on the decline and 72 from decent midfield time is very low for a former Pick 1, but as a MID-only he hasn't got the upside anymore especially as the Suns look for alternatives inside
Outside wingman with three straight seasons of regression, there's some value there but not as a MID-only with no CBAs

Comment: Bailey has something special about him. However, he might be one of those who are better in real life than in Fantasy, showcased by a career high average of 75, despite having big impact in some games. The Lions need someone like him to take the next step into the midfield, and he spent more time in their post-bye last year (32%) but that didn't result in a boost in scoring. He did get a 112 when McCluggage missed in Round 14 and he managed 45% CBAs, but it looks like he's not going to make a permanent midfield move anytime soon.
Short: Better in real life than Fantasy, especially if he remains in this forward/mid role
33-year-old key forward who tops out at the 70 mark

Comment: After averaging 98 post-bye in 2022 following a move to defence, Himmelberg was discussed as an option given he was priced at 80. However, Kinglsey decided to put him back to the forward-line to start the season, and he averaged 60 through eight rounds. The Giants had just two wins and needed to change something up. It was Round 9 where Himmelberg was moved back to defence, however it ended early, out with concussion in the first quarter. So by the time he returned in Round 12, he had an average of 56. From there, he remained in defence and averaged 86. The 98 from 2022 was always going to be a reach, given the more direct style played under Kingsley and that Whitfield and Ash were both used in defence in 2023, so Himmelberg had to share the load. It's been said that the Giants are going to settle Himmelberg as a defender in 2024, which is great news for his Fantasy prospects and means he's 15+ points under-priced. However, the early bye in Round 3 means it's hard to do, but he's someone to keep an eye on as an early upgrade.
Short: Didn't hit the heights he did post-bye in 2022 (110), but averaged 86 when moved to defence in 2023 and said to be staying there in 2024

Comment: Lukosius returned to the forward-line in 2022 after looking great as a running defender the year prior to average 86. His Fantasy output felt it, averaging 64 and 72. If Dimma keeps him as a forward, then you can rule him out of Fantasy calculations. If he moves back to defence, where he showed shades of a young Lachie Whitfield, then he could come into calculations but now as a starting option given that early bye.
Short: Averaged 86 in 2021 when used as a distributor down back but settled as a forward the last two seasons, interesting to see what Hardwick will do with him
I thought he'd struggle for midfield opportunity last year, but the evergreen 33-year-old averaged 88 from 71% CBAs in L5, still not enough to consider at that price, bye and age

Comment: The former Pick 6 had some stints in the midfield last season. He averaged 47% CBAs for the first six rounds of the season and gave the Crows a nice injection of pace in the middle. In that time, he averaged 92 points. Surprisingly, he averaged just 12% CBAs for the rest of the season and 64 Fantasy points. They preferred Rory Sloane, Ben Keays and later Matt Crouch in there ahead of him. I've said before the Crows' midfield is a little one-paced, especially a few years ago when they were running with Laird, Crouch, Berry, Schoenberg and Sloane. Dawson's move in there last year proved a masterstroke and he provided the point of difference, plus they look to have moved on from Berry and Schoenberg. But I think there is still room for the young Rachele to add some spark, and if we get an indication in the pre-season that he'll get 40%+ CBAs, then he could be the mid-priced forward we're hunting for in a season where we're going to have to punt on more midfield time for a lot of the forwards.
Short: Got a taste of the midfield early in 2023 with 47% CBAs in first six, dropped off as the season went on but I think the Crows need him in there more
Gun key forward but limited in Fantasy

Comment: If you've watched Gaff the last three seasons, it's hard to believe he's had multiple seasons over 110. He actually increased his scoring as the CBAs reduced towards the end of the year and I doubt we'll see him in there much at all in 2024, but regardless, it's hard to see him bouncing back to a level worth owning this season.
Short: Hard to believe Gaff was once a premium in this game

Comment: Ross has shown a bit when given the opportunity and dominated at reserve level (113 average from three games in 2023, 116 average from three games in 2021) so I think he's got potential to belong at AFL level at one point. However, he's yet to have a proper crack as a midfielder so far. The recruitment of Taranto and Hopper last season didn't help, with Ross attending just 2% of centre bounces for the season. Yze has flagged positional changes, so there's a chance we see Ross get more opportunity in 2024. But it would be too much of a risk at this price point.
Short: Some high scores at VFL level, just hasn't had the inside opportunity at AFL

Comment: Flynn has played 33 games in eight seasons and never played more than 12 in a season. He's always competed for the ruck role at the Giants but now finds himself at West Coast where he should start as their number 1. We've had a decent look at him in that role when he's had the opportunity and he's averaged around the 70 mark and 90s at VFL level. I think he'll get a bit of a boost with some continuity, but I doubt it will be enough to be a worthwhile selection in Fantasy. 27 Feb Update: Will miss 10-12 weeks after surgery to repair a tendon in his hamstring.
Short: A move to West Coast should see him have a proper run at number one ruck after being in the merry-go-round at the Giants, he might surprise a few, that was before a pre-season hamstring which will see him miss the start

Comment: After being used as a forward and midfielder in his early years, Blakey has now found his own playing as a dashing half-back. He took over the kick-in duties from Jake Lloyd, which shows how much the Swans wanted the ball in his hands and they used him at every opportunity. However, 48 games in the role for a very consistent average of 73, I'd need to see multiple 100+ scores before thinking he can elevate his Fantasy game to the next level.
Short: Second season above 70 in the running defender role, that might be his peak

Comment: Despite an injured eye-socket limiting him to 13 games last season, Stanley still finished the year at the Cats' preferred ruck option, playing nine of the last 10 games at 83% CBAs. With Conway waiting in the wings and Cats' needing to inject some youth into their side in 2024, I wouldn't be surprised to see the 33-year-old pushed out of the side this season.
Short: Surely this is the season they move on from Stanley

Comment: After three terrible seasons where he was injured, in and out of the team and was experimented in different roles, Milera returned to defence last season and showed signs of the 2018 season where he averaged 93 in the last five games. He got better as the season went on, increasing his time on ground, kick-in responsibilities and output as his confidence grew. He looks to have locked up that half-back role for the future, and the 83 he averaged in the L5 games is an indication of what he'll produce going forward. While that makes him slightly underpriced heading into 2024, I doubt he's going to boost his scoring to a level that would make him a worthwhile selection at that price, especially with the hamstring issues he has in the pre-season.
Short: Moved back to the HB role in 2023 and got better as the season went on, 83 in L5, but hamstring issues in the pre-season will mean a slow start

Comment: Hollands never got his chance at the Suns after being drafted Pick 7. He managed 118 late in 2022 and looked to have locked away a wing but managed just nine games the following season. Hopefully he gets a chance now he's at the Blues, but he's going to have an interrupted start.
Short: Has shown flashes of talent in the past, but missing the first two weeks and then the early bye will mean a slow start to the season

Comment: The former number 11 pick has been a regular for the Swans since his second season, playing over 90% of the games since. I thought he was a breakout candidate in 2020 after averaging 90 points in his final five games of 2019, however he's stagnated from there. This is on the back of a big drop in CBAs, where he took 69% in the first half of 2020 to 0% last season, where he settled on a half-back flank. Normally a natural midfielder-turned-defender is a recipe for high scoring, but with Blakey and Lloyd taking the majority of the distribution back there, Florent's scoring has remained around the 70 mark. There is scope for some improvement, but with those two still around, I doubt it will consistently be enough.
Short: After looking like a future midfielder with 52% CBAs in 2020, he's now purely a defender (0% CBAs in 2023) in a side with a lot of mouths to feed back there

Comment: Fiorini has always shown Fantasy ability, right from his debut season where he averaged 112 in four games at competition leading points-per-minute. He's since struggled for regular games, with the knock on him being he's not very damaging by foot and a bit one-paced. He managed 17 games last season, but mainly restricted to a wing role which doesn't really suit his style. He did average 59% CBAs in the final two matches of the season but didn't really make the most of his chances, scoring 86 and 90. A new coach aways gives hope, but even the most optimistic wouldn't expect to see Fiorini in the starting midfield mix at the Suns in 2024.
Short: Obvious Fantasy ability with 138 in VFL last year (135 year prior), just unlikely to have the role at AFL level

Comment: After averaging 80 in the last five games of 2021 and 107 in the AAMI, it looked like McInerney was going to breakout in 2022 in the wing/half-back role left vacant by Jordan Dawson. However, it's been purely wing since, which isn't as good for his Fantasy prospects, especially when Gulden takes up all the usage on the other wing.
Short: A handy winger but most the play goes through the Gulden wing instead

Comment: MacDonald entered the comp with a reputation of being a high production midfielder, his 121 average at NAB League was second only to Nick Daicos. He's obviously impressed as he debuted in Round 1 and managed to play 40 games in his first two seasons. So far, he's been limited to a small forward role. I expected him to see some midfield time last season following the departures of Mitchell and JOM, however it never eventuated. He showed great improvement over the year, despite the limited role, averaging 65 pre-bye, 77 post and 87 in his L5. In a year that's short on forwards, an 87 average for a forward priced at 71 would prove a great starting pick. He can obviously score, getting 37 touches and 126 points in his one VFL game last year. However, I doubt he can average 87 across a full season if he remains as a pure forward. CBAs in the pre-season matches are the key, if 40+, I think I'd start him, but I'd need to see some level of centre bounce attendance.
Short: A buzz name in the pre-season due to weak forwards, scoring at lower level, L5 of 87 and natural development

Comment: The Carlton swingman finally had a good run at it last season, playing 22 matches. He looked to have settled as an intercept defender and surprisingly took 62% of the Blues' kick-ins post-bye, ahead of Saad, Newman and Docherty. That still only led to a 77 average, which isn't close to the top six defenders in Fantasy.
Short: A full season after multiple injuries and surprisingly the preferred kicker for the Blues lead to a 70 average

Comment: Was drafted as one of the premier midfielders of the 2020 draft, so after settling with a forward role at the Giants, it was expected he would get his chance at the Cats who, despite being the reigning premiers, were pretty light on in the middle. He arrived at Geelong, who despite being the reigning premiers, they weren't super deep in the mids. He got off to a great start and was very impressive in both pre-season games with a clear inside mid role. He then started well in Round 1, scoring 29 at QT, but was then pushed to a wing after Tom Stewart was subbed off. He played 64% TOG that night, then 62% in R2 and 58% R3, none of them sub-impacted games, and then was dropped in R4. This was the story of his season, tastes of inside minutes with 49% CBAs but just 63% TOG. He scored 111 in the VFL game, making it six career VFL games over 100 out of 10, so I think he has the ability. I also think Geelong need to buy into their rebuild and give players like Bruhn more opportunity. However, I'm not confident it will happen so while he's a breakout candidate, I'm not 100% sold on him.
Short: Had a taste of midfield time in his first season at the Cats but CBA and TOG always capped, boost this year?

Comment: Corey Wagner was on both North Melbourne and Melbourne's list before being picked up by Freo from the VFL where he averaged 84. He got off to a shaky start, playing two games in the first six weeks and then not playing again until Round 18. However, he played the final seven games at an average of 77. That's about his level, but given his scrappy foot-skills, I'm not sure he'll be a lock in Freo's 22 each week.
Short: Mature age draftee took a while to find his groove back at AFL level but played the last seven at an average of 77

Comment: Harmes is coming off an average of 47 where played just nine games (was sub on three occasions). He's been a solid Fantasy contributor in the past, averaging 74 in 2022, 80 in 2021 and 94 in 2019. So when he arrived at the Dogs with forward status, he gained immediate interest. However, under the AFL Fantasy pricing method, if a player plays less than 10 matches, they are priced at a discount to the higher of their prior two seasons, which for Harmes is the 74 in 2022. Therefore, he's not as cheap as he is in SuperCoach, and while he'll stay on the radar as we know he can score well enough in the right role, I doubt he'll be relevant in Fantasy this year. 23 Feb Update: The inside mid role appears real and he's had a great pre-season. Maybe an 80 average is enough in the forward line this season which is certainly achievable in the high-scoring Dogs' system. I still have doubts he'll keep the CBA role with the talent the Dogs have, so I'm still not as keen as others.
Short: Now at the Dogs and who knows what Bevo has planned for him, if it's a midfield role he can return to his 75+ ways but that's about what he's priced at

Comment: Perryman had been a reliable wing/midfielder for the Giants since 2019, averaging 85+ for the three season to 2022 and slowly spent some more time inside (including a season high 114 from 51% CBAs in the first game after Leon left). He started in the opening centre bounce of 2023, however injured his hamstring in the opening minutes on 2, forcing him to miss the next four weeks. He returned in Round 6 and had 79% CBAs, so he was obviously in Kingsley's plans to play as a midfielder. However, he moved back to defence after Round 10, seeing CBAs in just one other match for the season. This coincided with Giants getting on a roll, so you'd think he will remain in that role in 2024. He averaged 74 in this time, so while he comes into 2024 with defender status, discounted due to his early injury and 18 points below his career best, it's unlikely he'll improve on his 2023 average if his post-bye role and scoring are anything to go by. 18 Feb Update: Pre-season hamstring injury will see him start slowly.
Short: Returned to defence post-bye when Giants started to roll, so you'd think his wing/midfield days are done along with those 85+ scores

Comment: Stocker got a lifeline from the Saints and was great for them in 2023, playing 23 matches as a small defender. While he showed a ceiling, he's behind Sinclair, NWM and even Battle for distribution and limited to a defensive role. Saints do possess the ball in their D50 which will keep his score up, but it's hard to see him improving much on his 2023 average.
Short: Career best season playing 23 games and showed a ceiling with 127, but low in the pecking order for distribution at the Saints
Averaged 70 last season having a terrific year IRL, it's hard to see him reaching much higher

Added plenty to the Giants after missing the entire 2022 season, pushes up to stoppages so he scores better than the average small forward but I doubt he's ever going to make the genuine midfield transition needed to be relevant in this game
Terrible injury history, however he had his first consistent season with 17 matches and showed great signs intercepting in defence, but scoring isn't there as a key defender

Comment: Elliot Yeo was a Fantasy premium in 2018 averaging 106, making him the 12th highest scorer in the comp. He backed that up with a respectable 102 but then the dreaded OP struck, and he's missed more than 50% of games since and struggled with his output. A calf injury just before Round 1 after looking the goods as a midfielder in the pre-season games wasn't the ideal start. He then played two games before Round 11 after dealing with groin issues, averaging just 46. However, he started to find his groove, averaging 93 for the four games to Round 15, before hurting his hip - the trifecta! He went on to play four more games, but was managed throughout, including being used as the sub. All that together left with a 70 average for the season. If he's healthy, he can easily average 90+, whether that's as a defender in the absence of Shannon Hurn or as a mature inside mid. Him being healthy is the big question and a risk that anyone will take who pick him. You need to take risks to succeed in this game and if he has a healthy pre-season and looks good in the matches, then I'm ready to go back again. Update: He's fit (for now), he's full time mid and I'm on board.
Short: Hasn't played more than 12 games in the last four seasons so his body is always a concern, but if fully fit he's still a very good player IRL and Fantasy and all reports he is

Comment: After years on the fringe, Guthrie has now played 44 games in the last two seasons, cementing his spot in backline. He had some nice scoring games when Geelong play their high marking style in defence, but I doubt he’ll ever average enough to be considered in AFL Fantasy.
Short: Now a regular for the Cats but not one for Fantasy
Showed promise averaging 80 in just his third season, but never took the next step and now a MID-only now coming off a sub-60 average post-bye on a wing
Turned into a gun intercept defender IRL and shown a ceiling with Freo's high mark game in defence (2 scores over 120 in 2023), but a season average of 70 isn't enough to consider
Crazy to think he averaged 107 in 2018, now 30 and with the Saints looking to add more speed, he might struggle for opportunity in 2024

Comment: Baker does a bit of everything for the Tigers, playing forward, back and even in the middle. He can excel at all of them and if we knew he would remain a defender or a mid then we might be able to trust him in Fantasy. Yze has flagged positional changes, so despite the inconsistency to date, he's on my watchlist for the pre-season. He's a far better player than his career best average of 73. 18 Feb Update: Said to be playing midfield this season, we've seen him thrown around before and with the early bye, I'd rather trade into him when I get confidence in role and scoring, but I've bumped him up a bit in Draft.
Short: He can certainly play, but too hard to predict where he'll play week-to-week, maybe we'll get some consistency with role in 2024 and he beats that 73 career best average

Comment: There was a bit of buzz around Lipinski when he arrived at the Pies. He showed great signs from limited opportunities at the Dogs and put up some monster scores at VFL level. He led the Pies for CBAs in the pre-season game and then scored 117 from 48% CBAs in Round 1. However, he didn't go on with it and dropped to 19% in his last five of 2023. He was completely pushed out of the midfield last season, attending just 3% CBAs for an average of 70. The structure obviously worked as the Pies went on to win the flag. Adams is gone but he didn't see many CBAs either, so I doubt Lipinski will get back in the middle in 2024.
Short: Forward status is nice but doubt he'll get the midfield opportunities he needs to be a top six as he had just 3% last year when Pies won the flag
Gun key forward, just not Fantasy relevant with an average of 70 in his last three seasons

Comment: Coleman moved to defence in 2022 after averaging 109 in the role at reserve level in 2021. He showed he has the makings to be a star defender of the future, but injures stopped him from a full breakout. The story was much the same in 2023. He was concussed in Round 1 on 57, forcing him to miss Round 2. He returned to average just 61 in his next nine to the bye, looking a shadow of the player that broke out a year earlier. He was so far out of form that he started as sub post-bye, which is where he scored his 23. After that, he was quoted saying "I just thought to myself to back myself. That’s when I play my best footy, when I’m just out there, playing freely and playing on instinct". And he did. He averaged 90 in his last seven matches, which included another injury (eye) when saw him sit off just after half time and miss two more matches. He then went to another level in the finals, averaging 102, including a best on ground performance in the prelim and 22 disposals to half time (over 100) in the GF. While Rich was a non-factor last year, his retirement means that Coleman is now the number one distributor for the Lions, a role which can yield an 85+ average. If it weren't for the Round 2 bye, I'd be prepared to start with him. Now I think you need a 100+ score in Round 0 to make the cash gen worthwhile, knowing he's missing the second week.
Short: Interrupted 2023 but his finish caught the eye (95 in L2, 102 in finals) and he comes in as a great discounted defender, if it wasn't for that Round 2 bye
Handy scorer for a key defender (helps that he takes 61% of the KI - not many full-backs do that) but not enough to make him relevant
Has played a vital role as a hard running small forward at West Coast for a number of years now, just not a great role for Fantasy scoring
Sounds like a forward role for Hind this season which will hurt his upside

Comment: Sam Berry looked like he was the future of the Crow's midfield, playing prime midfield minutes in his second season over the likes of leadership group member Ben Keays and former B&F winner Matt Crouch. He led the comp in tackles per game, which was a great achievement for a 21-year-old in his first full season in the midfield. However, Berry's 17.6 disposals per game was low for a main midfielder and with Laird already offering tackle pressure (number two on the tackle list that year), the Crows looked to add some more speed and dynamic movement in there last season. That meant Berry spent most of the year playing SANFL, with just four games at AFL level after 35 in his first two seasons. Laird and Dawson are locked into the midfield and they opted for Crouch as the third mid to finish 2023. I doubt much will change this season, but hopefully we see more of Berry in 2024. Regardless, he's priced at a discount to his 2022 average, meaning he's priced at 69, so he's not super value even if he does get back into the side.
Short: An 84 in his second season looked like he'd be a future Fantasy stud, but the Crows have gone quicker inside now and even if he gets his chance in 2024, the pricing system doesn't make him a bargain

Comment: Once a star IRL, but struggled with form and injury at the Dons. He's had foot and knee surgery in the off-season and together with the number of young mids emerging at the Essendon, I doubt we see him in their midfield again.
Short: Out of favour at the Dons who now have plenty of young options to take the midfield spots

Comment: Fisher could never quite crack it at the Blues, despite being always spoken of highly by key members of the team. He was traded to North in the off-season in a trade that could really unlock his potential. After playing just one of 13 games from Round 8, the small forward came back into the side in Round 21 as a running half-back. He had 32 disposals in that game and remained there for the next 3, before being dropped for finals. Around the trade, Fisher noted that Clarkson earmarked him to play as a running defender at the Roos as they look to add to their run and carry game. We've seen the primary Roo defender rack up Fantasy points in recent years, from Luke McDonald in 2020, Jack Ziebell and Aaron Hall in 2021 and Harry Sheezel last season. With Hall and Ziebell retired and Sheezel a chance to progress into the midfield, Fisher is every chance to land that role. At his price, even the 86 he averaged at the Blues in the role would make him a good mid-priced selection as that's not going to be far behind the F6. Update: That role was there but he's now had two hamstring issues which is a red flag, I am okay taking on an injury risk like Yeo, but interrupted pre-season is another issue. 23 Feb Update: Made some errors and didn't have it all to himself with Sheez and Mckerch back there, but Fisher featured in a HB role in the pre-season game and gathered enough of the ball. Back on the radar if he gets through the next match.
Short: Might not have seemed like much at the time, but could be a very relevant off-season move if he lands himself in the plumb distribution role at the Roos, though multiple hamstring issues in the pre-season is a red flag
A gun full-back of the comp but not a relevant pick in this game, unless your draft settings value spoils
Better IRL than in Fantasy, Quaynor is a gun small defender but yet to show he's much of an accumulator so his scoring is limited

Comment: Cumming dropped his averaged by 23 points in 2023, which was amazing given there was no injury and he was heading into his age 24 season, meaning he should be in his prime. Cumming averaged 91 in 2022 and his breakout 2021, quickly becoming the Giants' number one distributor down back as Leon played Ash on the ball and Whitfield up forward. Kingsley came in and put things straight, with Whitfield and Ash back in defence and later Himmelberg who moved back to finish the season. This pushed Cumming up to a wing, which as we know isn't a good thing for Fantasy scoring. He averaged 65 post-bye and didn't take a kick-in to finish the year. This coincided with the Giants' best form of the year, so I'm not sure there is a spot for Cumming in defence in 2024, at least not the high distribution role he had in 2022. I'm not banking on a large bounce back this season at least. 18 Feb Update: Pre-season quad injury will see him start slowly.
Short: Not many 25-year-olds drop 23 points per game without an injury, has to bounce back but no longer the main distributor with Whitfield, Ash and Himmelberg back now
Struggled to get on the park since 2019, his best is decent for a key back but even that wouldn't be enough

Comment: JHF impressed in his first season at the Power. He arrived after one season at the Roos where he had 40% CBAs. With Wines, Boak, Butters, Rozee and Drew, I doubted he would see more than this for a team in contention, however he finished with 59% CBAs to be a clear first-choice midfielder. If you're looking at pure disposal stats, you'd say he had a modest season, averaging less than 18 touches per game. However, he finished the year with 16 Brownlow votes, the same as sensation Tom Green. He tore some games apart with his clearance work and penetration inside 50 from stoppages. However, you don't get extra points for that in Fantasy and what he lacked was easy possessions. He has 13 games sub-70 and seven sub-50. He's yet to have a full pre-season, so maybe that explains why he doesn't do much outside of a stoppage. But he's in the Patrick Dangerfield mould, and Danger took four seasons before he averaged over 71. I expect him to add some more disposals to his game this year. However, with Wines hoping to spend more time inside also, I don't think we'll see a significant bump from JHF this year.
Short: Clear talent but in the high-impact low-posession bucket at the moment, his first full pre-season might see him win more ball, but I think he'll need a few more years before his best

Comment: The former top 10 pick averaged 84 in the second half of his 2nd season and was heavily involved in centre bounces. He hasn't come on from there, failing to average above 80. He’s also had a shocking run of injuries, and while he managed 19 matches last season, he missed six weeks in the middle with a knee injury when he was on 3. He was also sub on a few occasions, with four games under 50% TOG. The positive was that he was injected back into the midfielder, with 31% CBAs from his 58% season TOG. The downside is that he lost his defender status, which is what kept him on my radar his whole career. A clean run of injury will see a nice improvement in output in 2024, as his ranked 98th in price yet 36th for points per minute. But he's too risky of a play as a MID-only option.
Short: Has ability but battled with injuries his whole career and now lost the defender status that always kept him relevant

Comment: Sholl finished 2020 with an adjusted 110 and 84 and was the designated kicker at the Crows. He then had a 102, 103 and 130 in his first five games of 2021 and looked to be a serious player of the future. It all went downhill from there and Sholl has struggled for senior opportunities since. I've seen enough to believe he'll be a player in the future, but as a midfield only option in Fantasy he's not an option this year.
Short: Wing with MID-only status and still yet to cement his spot in the team

Comment: I just like the way this guy goes about it and was surprised he was pushed out of the midfield rotation for the likes of Crouch and Keays to finish the season. I think he's a star of the future, but it won't be this year if he stays at 9% CBAs. I wouldn't start with him, but just keep him on your radar. A pre-season ankle injury might delay that further.
Short: I really like this guy and he could be the breakout player we're chasing, but MID-only for someone who had 9% CBAs post-bye makes it hard
Key defender with limited scoring

Comment: The number nine pick of the 2020 draft has played an impressive 61 games in his first two seasons, providing some x-factor around goal and in the air. He’s been tested in the middle at times and looked okay, but I would've expected more than 62 from his 39% CBAs post-bye. He just doesn't look like a big ball winner. The Bombers have a number of players who run through there, and I currently have Perkins behind Hobbs and Caldwell ahead of him, so I can't see him keeping up that 39%. However, with his forward status he’s worth keeping an eye on.
Short: A watch on his CBAs in pre-season and forward status makes him relevant, but we could say that about a number of Bombers
Drafted top 10 in 2018 as a midfielder, although limited to defence and the wing at AFL and scoring hasn’t been there consistently
One of the best restrictive small defenders in the comp, but not in a scoring friendly role
Star key forward but scoring will always be limited
Genuine role player in defence who has capped out at the 70 mark
Star small forward hasn't done much more than 70 in that role, but supposedly training as a half-back which could provide a small boost

Comment: Was said to be the premier midfielder and the most ready to play from the 2020 draft pool. Phillips for Oakleigh averaged better numbers at the same age during the finals than Matt Rowell and Noah Anderson. However, he didn't look it in his first season, averaging 44 in his 14 games. He then missed the entire 2022 season due to glandular fever, but completed a full pre-season in 2023. He got enough opportunity, 16 games at 62% CBAs, however, didn't take the jump I was hoping he would. The Roos' midfield developing nicely, I wouldn't be surprised to see Philips on the outer in 2024.
Short: Highly credentialed junior was finally fully fit in 2023 after glandular ruined his 2022 season, however, didn’t show much and might be overtaken by the new batch of Roo mids
On a wing now and that combined with his age means he's not the 80+ scorer of the past

Comment: Jones has been used as a dashing half-back for the depleted West Coast side in the last two seasons and showed flashes of decent scoring, including an 84 average from Round 4-8. I like him there and think he adds something different to a Witherden and Hough type, but there's no certainty of his spot in the side so it's hard to take a punt on him, especially with a pre-season hamstring.
Short: Averaged 84 from Round 4-8 before injury stuck and he might find it harder this season as WC have a healthier list

Comment: Draper is a ruck who is better IRL than in Fantasy. In fact, he's only ever scored the one score over 90 in his career. He might see more than 66% CBAs now that Phillips has retired, but then again Goldy might be the preferred man. Judging from his scoring to date, it's hard to see him making an impact in Fantasy, despite ruckmen typically hitting their peak at age 25.
Short: I know even the best Fantasy rucks take time, but Draper has now had seven seasons at AFL level and yet to average 70, an interrupted pre-season isn't going to help either

Comment: Sparrow has been getting midfield opportunities in a strong midfield since his debut. The scoring hasn't followed suit, averaging 67 from 46% CBAs in 2023 after 63 from 32% CBAs in 2022. He's obviously highly rated and there is more time up for grabs with Jordon and Harmes gone and Oliver's situation, however I doubt we will see his scoring spike much more than 75.
Short: Mid-forward who gets CBAs but yet to show a scoring game

Comment: Scrim has a Fantasy game that I thought would see him be a top six defender before his career is done. However, he's now 25 and yet to average over 80. His teammates have scored well in a similar role, and I think have moved past him now, so I'm now less bullish.
Short: I've been a fan of the former top 10 pick for a few years now, but he just hasn't delivered, starting to lose hope
At his best, the interceptor pushed the top 6, but hasn't been that way for a while now and five sub games in 2023 indicate they might have moved past him
Even when number one ruck he wasn’t a Fantasy scorer and I think the Blues prefer Pitbull in CBAs as they did as the season went on
One of the best small forwards in the comp but still not one for Fantasy, despite the fact he takes CBAs of those that are relevant
Yet to match his brilliant debut season, a new team might provide a fresh start but with MID-only, it's not worth punting on the bounce back
A reliable defender but scoring is capped at 70
Key forward/ruck who had his best year to date, but scoring won't be enough
Struggled with injury and other health issues in 2023 so scoring was down, can definitely outperform his price but probably not by enough to be relevant

Comment: Campbell showed a lot of promise early as a rookie, scoring 96 in his second game. He's got a terrific kick on him and showed enough for me to think he'll be a player of the future. However, he played 23 matches last season and averaged just 66, so I think it will be a while before he comes Fantasy relevant with Blakey and Lloyd controlling things down back.
Short: Elite kick and has talent, but yet to show much in the scoring department so far
Back after two years overseas last season and looked as good as ever, but that just yields a 65-point average
Can play forward, back, and ruck and it looks like he's settled in the least scoring-friendly role, defence

Comment: Zurhaar is a bash and crash forward, a powerful athlete and shares some (very minor) similarities with Petracca. A move to the midfield has always been on the cards and that evolution started last year with a career high 22% CBAs. It didn't lead to a spike in scoring, increasing his average by six to 65. He's reportedly much leaner this season and set for a big season, but we've heard that before. If anything I can see him being a high impact mid/forward, but I doubt he's suddenly going to become an accumulator.
Short: We've been waiting for the strong forward to make a 'Petracca' midfield move, which kind of happened last year to no real effect but supposedly has stripped fitter this season

Comment: Really liked what I saw from Weddle, both defensively and his rebound from defence and there is plenty of high praise for him coming out of Hawthorn. The Hawks have found one. However, it's hard to rely on a rebounding defender who doesn't take kick-ins and is behind Sicily, Hardwick and Amon for distribution. One for the future.
Short: Terrific debut season and a player for the future, natural improvement should come but still behind a few for distribution so he's hard to rely on
Found more opportunity with Amon leaving, playing a career high 22 games, but scoring remained in the 60s

Comment: After sitting behind Goldstein for many years, it looked like North had finally decided to look to the future when they named Xerri sole ruck in Round 1 and Goldy emergency. After getting off to a flyer (26 points in 15% TOG), he did his syndesmosis and missed the next 15 weeks. After a 113 in the VFL, he returned to the senior side again as sole ruck, seeing 84% CBAs for a 110. At that stage, he led all rucks for points per minute, ahead of English and Marshall. He was sole ruck the following week but found things tougher against the Reeves/Meek duo (many did in 2023) and scored 74. However he was never solo again, averaging 43% CBAs for the final six matches sharing with Goldy. Goldy has now been moved on and we should see Xerri solo for 2024. He has the scoring ability and now should have the opportunity and with no early bye like the other value ruck plays (Gawn and Grundy), I'm in favour of Xerri at R2. Update: face surgery will keep him out of contact training for a few weeks, but he should still be able to keep up his fitness.
Short: Started Round 1 sole ruck but an early injury meant he never had a proper crack at it, with Goldy now gone, it's Xerri time
Amazing season finishing 7th in the Coleman and still averaged 64 shows how low key forwards score in this game

Comment: After averaging 84 in his second season, Burton looked to be a star Fantasy defender of the future. He hasn't matched that average since. Unfortunately, he hasn't come on and you can't take the risk on him turning it around this year.
Short: Hasn't come on as I thought he was going to after his 84 average in year 2

Comment: So far in his career, he's been more of an impact player than an accumulator, which is never a great thing for Fantasy scoring. We've all been waiting for him to pop and be the explosive, goal-kicking mid the Lions are crying out for, but just 8% CBAs last year after 24% the year before, the Lions might now see him as just a forward. Even if those CBAs rise, I'd want to see some sign of scoring improvement first. 10 Feb Update: Sounds like the midfield move is going to happen, I've moved him up slightly but nothing of note just yet.
Short: Still waiting for the breakout and CBAs just 8% after 24% the season prior not a good sign
The junior stud with Rockliff-like NAB League numbers has been limited to a small forward role at AFL level (0% CBAs in last two seasons) and hard to see that changing
Had a huge improvement in his first year at the Giants but small forward roles aren't friendly for scoring
Star small forward but scoring limited to sub-70
Star key defender in real life, not in Fantasy
Role player for the Blues not in Fantasy calculations, unfortunately has done an ACL and will miss the season
Limited to a 60 average while in the forward role and given how good he is at it, I doubt we'll see him back on the wing or half-back again
Regular role player in defence for the Saints but never taken his game to the next level in Fantasy
Very good footballer but scoring limited as a small forward, so unless he make a move to the midfield which he's teased at times, he's not going to make an impact in Fantasy

Comment: Saints look like they got a steal with Windhager, taken pick 47 of the 2021 draft. After an impressive debut season, Windhager was made to work for his opportunities in his second season. A broken hand in the pre-season match saw him miss Round 1 and then start as the sub in Round 2. He was sub in three of his first six matches before being dropped to the VFL. It's here he showed his scoring power, scoring 98, 157, 91 and 120 in his four matches. This shouldn’t come as a great surprise considering he scored over 110 twice in three games at the level in 2022. He was back in the senior side in Round 13 and didn't miss a game after that. He moved to half-back in Round 17 and played there for the final nine games of the season, averaging 79. Personally I found the move odd as the one knock on him is his kicking, he's certainly better suited inside mid. However, it means he has defender status heading into 2024 and if the inside mid move happens, he could prove one of the value picks of the season. Even if it doesn't there's 20-point upside given what he showed as a defender, but I think you want a tad more than that at that price. 23 Feb Update: Broke his hand early in the pre-season game. Said to be right by Round 1, but now how are we going to know if he's got a midfield role? He was there for the short period prior to the injury which is a good sign, but the risk of the pick has increased now. Might have to be someone we trade into unless we hear/see something positive.
Short: Played a bit of everywhere in his first two seasons and shown above average ability, I'm a believer I just need to see his role in the pre-season
Had his best season in five years but not enough to be relevant
Small forward who has been used in spurts in the middle, but scoring is still capped at sub-70

Comment: Bit of buzz coming out of the Dons on this kid, I don’t know how they are going to fit them all in, but I have bumped him up slightly.
Short: A 2021 mid-season draft pick has made the wing his own, much loved by Bomber supporters but scoring is limited on the wing
Evergreen 35-year-old full forward is still playing well IRL but not the combo you want in Fantasy
Has talent but hovers around the 60-mark every season
Ignore the discount to career high (which was four games in the 16-min quarters), he plays a more defensive role nowadays
Had some good games last season for someone who was delisted the re-rookied, but scoring wasn't enough to consider this season

Injuries kept him to just eight matches last season, priced at a discount to his 2022 average means there's not enough value there even if he returns to his best - pre-season hamstring will see him miss time
Small forward who played 22 matches last season, but role isn't what you want in Fantasy
