Horror season playing four matches before injury ruled him out, priced at 62 which he should outperform by 10+, but I never like picking key forwards

Comment: After a very impressive first season and a 125 in Round 2 of his second, it appeared that Bowey could be a Fantasy gem. However, he's yet to replicate that output at AFL level since, averaging just 63 in the last two seasons. He’s showed enough to suggest he’s going to be a gun in the future, but he’s behind a few at the Dees so it won’t be for a few years yet.
Short: Showed flashes of scoring potential in his 47 games to date but just doesn't do it regularly enough
Rallied strongly since being delisted and re-rookied but consecutive seasons averaging low-60s isn't what we're after
35-year-old has been a gun in the past - IRL and Fantasy - but will again play a mentor role at the Power
Disappointing last two seasons after a career best 2021 - form, fitness and role too hard to predict
Key position player and scoring is stuck in the 60-70 range
His 101 VFL average in 2022 didn't translate to the AFL in 2023 as he spent most of the season on the wing
Genuine role player, either in defence or as a tagger, and scoring has never been relevant

Comment: After an impressive debut season, Hough took a while to find his groove in 2023 with injury keeping him to two games after the first eight rounds. He then played all bar two the rest of the season, which included two scores 105+, which is impressive given his age, role (defender with 1% KI) and how poor West Coast were. Shannon Hurn retiring is going to open up a lot of distribution opportunities down back at West Coast and Hough could well be the one who benefits. At that price point, it's hard to take a punt on him though, but he could be one for the future.
Short: Has displayed a nice kick-mark game in his first two seasons and with Hurn's departure freeing up some distribution, we could see him get a nice bump in 2024
Settled in a defensive forward role now and plays it to great effect, so the days of waiting for the midfield move might be over
The wing/half-forward has a bit about him and I think he can be a good player, but not a Fantasy one if he continues in those roles
A role change last season from a reliable 70/80s defender to a pressure forward wasn't good for his Fantasy output and even if he switches back his upside isn't enough

Comment: There has been limited exposed form for Wardlaw over the last two year, but what we have seen has been outstanding. He was limited to just four games in his draft year due to hamstring injuries but of those, was best on ground in Round 1 and BOG again in the AFL Academy game. He was on a modified pre-season program and didn't debut until Round 10, but it was one of the better debuts you'll see - 16 touches, six clearances and nine tackles from 63% TOG. He backed it up in Round 13 with 22 touches, six clearances and nine tackles from 70% TOG and 22 touches and seven tackles from 68% in Round 16. However, he was a late out Round 17 and subbed out in Round 18 and then played just the one more game for the year where he again had nine tackles in 55% TOG. In all he finished the season with eight matches at just 60% TOG. He's now had his first full pre-season under his belt which should see him bump up to at least 70% TOG. At the same PPM, he would average 78, which isn't enough. Daicos' 2nd year breakout was another level given he came off a high base but Clayton Oliver and Tim Taranto were at a similar price point where you can afford to wait to see how they look (role, TOG, score) in the early rounds and trade them in if they tick the boxes. That's how I'd play it I think.
Short: Caught the eye in limited opportunities in his debut season and looks a future star, second year breakouts are rare but he's one who could be up to it
Medium forward with limited scoring opportunities

Comment: Graham appeared to be the next midfielder up once Cotchin, Prestia and Martin start to push out. And given his elite tackling ability and scoring at junior level, he's one I've kept an eye on. After averaging 84 from 40% CBAs in the last five of 2021, I expected that transition to continue. However, he went backwards, averaging 74 from just 22% CBAs in 2022 (incl. 49 from 1% in his last 5) and just 6% last season. A new coach provides hope that he might be seen in the middle again, but it's not a punt I'd be willing to take.
Short: Arrival of Taranto and Hopper quashed any hope of Graham stepping up in the midfield, but maybe the new coach will be the change he needs

Comment: Reeves proved the hardest ruck for opposition players to ruck against. He's a very strong hitout ruck, but struggles to impact around the ground which, between that and sharing the duties with Meek, caps his output.
Short: Meek arriving put question marks on his spot, but he emerged the preferred option and will likely be the Hawks' number one ruck to start, but will share duties at times which will cap his output
Wing/forward who has had his opportunities but has never scored well enough

Played 18 games in his first season at North but limited to a wing which is never good for scoring, has scored okay when inside in the past but with the young midfield depth developing at the Roos, I can't see him used there
Averaged 70 post-bye incl finals when his kick-in duties went from 3% to 21% and with some more confidence can improve again, but not to a level worth considering

Comment: Bowes was a prolific midfielder in juniors, averaging 118 points in the NAB League which saw him be a top 10 pick at the Suns, where he played predominantly in defence. He looked to arrive in 2021, averaging 95 in the first half but has battled with injury ever since. A hamstring injury stopped his breakout in 2021 and then surgery in the pre-season ruled him out for the first four months of 2022. He arrived at Geelong last season and looked to have a mid role in the first pre-season game before a hamstring injury saw him just play a half. After missing Round 1, he played five matches with only one with CBAs, but managed to score 77+ in four of them. He then hurt his calf on 10 and missed the next six weeks. He returned as sub for the next three matches, scoring 21, 54 and nine and then played a full game in defence for a 101. He failed to reach 90 in a game after that, but if you remove the four sub games he averaged 72. He's hard to read as is the Cats, who played him back, wing, on-ball and forward in 2023. If he can settle in a position he might prove a great pick, but he hasn't been reliable so far in his career so it's too risky for me.
Short: Didn't get the mid time we expected after moving to the Cats and even when he did, he didn't catch the eye, but a full pre-season and four sub games means he's underpriced heading into 2024
Likely out for the season with an Achilles
Become a decent forward after many wrote him off, but key forwards aren't what we're looking for
Small forward and getting on in age at 33
Not quite a key position player but scores like one
A lifeline at the Dogs saw him play 18 matches last season, but wing role kept his scoring in check
Key forward developing into a very nice player, but not in Fantasy
Managed to break in as a defender and looked the goods as a designated kicker, but scoring not enough to consider this season
Showed signs of why he was taken Pick 1 in 2020 and I feel like he could rip the comp apart this season, but breakouts for key position forwards aren't enough in this game
Former first rounder played every game in 2023 and highly rated, but might need some more time before we see constant scoring (23 games of 24 under 90)
Had an incredible year in a struggling side but still not scoring enough to be anywhere near relevant

Comment: Is there a 28-gamer that has had more airtime in Fantasy than Braydon Preuss? After missing his full first season at the Giants, Preuss averaged 94 points per full game played. It was the fact he only played 10 games and got injured/suspended/dropped throughout the year. Sadly, this has been the consistent story for Preuss his entire career and it allowed Briggs to take the number one mantle last season and run with it. There's no doubt he's a very good Fantasy scorer when on the park, but I think he'll just go back to dominating the VFL (107 last season, 132 in 2019).
Short: Had his chances but never took them and now Briggs has cemented the number one ruck role at the Giants
Outside wing who has amazingly averaged in the 60s the whole way through under Hardwick's style, might change with a new coach but as a MID-only he's not going to be an option
Gun key defender but is now 33 and hard to see a relevant jump in scoring

Comment: The former number three pick looked set to fulfill his potential in 2019, pushing up the ground to average 99 points per game, including 106 in the last half. Unfortunately, he hasn't gone on with it, dropping his average in every season since to finish on 61 last year from just three matches after a broken leg ruled him out for the first half of the season. At 28, he should be in his prime and may appear underpriced to what he could produce and an off-season move to the Dees might change things for him. It will be very interesting to see how the Dees use him. On the watch-list for the pre-season and I guess we'll get a proper indication in the opening round. But it's hard to see him averaging much more than 80 unless he runs through the midfield.
Short: Reduced his average every year since 2019 where he was a top six forward, a change of scenery might be what he needs to turn it around
Been on the radar since his elite junior numbers (124 average in NAB League) but limited to a forward role at AFL level and always on the fringe
Moved to Hawks last season for more opportunity but found himself playing second fiddle to Reeves, and given how good Reeves was, it will likely continue in 2024
Took the number one ruck mantle for finals and finished with a premiership, but that didn't lead to much of a bump in scoring
Retuned from an ACL to play 12 matches in 2023 but not as the midfielder he needs to be to be relevant in this game
A key position player who would score a bit higher if he kicked straighter, but not enough to make an impact
Been a good servant of all three teams but I think he'll struggle for opportunities this season with the young Roo mids emerging
74 in 2020 the outlier, he's been a mid-50s guy his whole career which is what you can expect from a small forward
Key defender who might see some more opportunity with Murray injured, but he scores like a full-back
Had some good games in 2023 and I think we'll see a lot more of him, but small forward role isn't conducive to scoring
General defender who outside his 2x100 scores in 2023, doesn't generate enough points to be relevant
Lock-down defender who is currently dealing with an ankle injury
Was preferred over TDK for number one ruck and proved hard to ruck against, but scoring limited
Scores okay in the ruck (season high 106 from season high 47% CBAs) and reportedly wants more time in there this season, but hard to see that happening when they have the All-Australian there
A small forward with a bit of energy about him, not one for the Fantasy scorers though
Will hope to bounce back from a career worst season but even best case won't be enough, especially with a pre-season hamstring

Comment: Former Pick 11 battled with injury in his first few seasons at the Crows but played 21 last season and looked the part with his strong body and skills. He was used primarily as a small forward, but was introduced to the midfield with 13% CBAs across the season. I think he's going to be a regular midfielder in the future, but I also think Rachelle and Soligo will. And Laird and Dawson aren't going anywhere this season. So while I think one of the young guns will breakout this season, I'm not sure I'm ready to punt on any of them.
Short: Another of the young Crow fwd/mids who has shown enough to suggest they will be future guns, and he was preferred over Rachelle and Soligo for CBAs in the backend of 2023
Showed amazing running power on the wing for a first-year player and can see him staying on the wing for the Blues for the future, which isn't great for his scoring
Hard running forward is a regular at Freo, but role isn't great for Fantasy
Dropped 11 points from his B&F season but even that wasn't worth owning in Fantasy

Comment: Ginbey was one of the few shining lights for West Coast in 2023. He was thrown in the deep end playing inside mid for a team who struggled most weeks, but it was a clear sign they have big wraps on the kid. He showed a great tackle ability (5.9 per game, in line with the top eight mids) and contested possession rate (46.4%, above that of the top eight mids), however struggled to win the ball outside the contest (13.7 disposals and 1.5 marks per game). That will come, but I doubt it will see a big spike in his second season. He's in great condition on the training track and I'm looking forward to seeing how he looks in the pre-season games, but out of the second year players, I don't think he's the one that will have the big impact.
Short: Big bodied mid has got even bigger this off-season and could certainly breakout, just not sure he has the outside game to be a worthy Fantasy option just yet
Will be a star key forward someday, but scoring isn't there
Back after three years out but will likely provide back-up to Nank and the pricing system doesn't mean he's a bargain
Medium forward who found a role on the wing to finish 2023, but scoring wasn't great
The strong tackling mid has been out with an ACL and expected to miss the start of 2024

Comment: Out of all the 2020 draftees, I was most impressed with Powell’s first season, which makes his last two seasons even more disappointing. The former Pick 13 averaged 68 in his first season after 35 disposals per game in SANFL Under-18s in his draft year. He's since been in and out of the side and averaged 56 points per game in the last two seasons. He got a bit of a bump in midfield time, which included 29% CBAs post-bye to net a 72 average. He will remain on the radar given he has forward status and talent at junior level, however with another batch of young players coming in at the Roos, it's going to be harder for him in 2024 to get the opportunity. However, he's apparently dominating the pre-season, so once again he's on my watchlist for 2024 - without a great deal of hope. 23 Feb Update: I've bumped him up again after an impressive pre-season showing in a CBA role.
Short: Another disappointing season after showing so many signs in his debut year, with another batch of young players coming in it's hard to keep hope, but somehow I still have some
Reliable key defender but unlikely scoring will change
Had a massive season back after returning from injury to be one of the best key backs in the comp, but far better in real life than in Fantasy
Small forward so scoring is limited, a bad hamstring injury in pre-season won't help either
Definition of a role player up forward for the Suns, and certainly not worried about scoring Fantasy points

Comment: Sheldrick is a contested ball winning bull who led the Under-19 Championships in contested possessions, so it was a surprise when Swans debuted him in Round 1 2022 as a small forward. He didn't play again at AFL level that season, but after a 158 at VFL level, he featured in Round 7 last season for the first time since. He was subbed out on just 18 and went back to the VFL where he scored a 130. He played again at AFL level in Round 10 where he started sub and scored just 8, and also played VFL that week for a 118. So while his career scores at AFL read 28, 18 and 8, he showed at the level below that he had something special. We then finally saw him get a decent run at AFL level, playing four games in a row at 91, despite playing just 64% TOG. He then did his syndesmosis in Round 17 on 46, and he didn't feature again. So on face value, he's priced at 57 (9% discount to his 62 average due to playing seven games) and he averaged 91 if you exclude his sub games and when he was injured and that was from just 64% TOG. The question is if he features in their starting midfield rotation now with Adams and Jordon arriving and Warner set for more time in there. If he does, then he might be the breakout candidate we're chasing. We'll get an idea of role, TOG and scoring in the opening round, but I feel he might be a year away. 27 Feb Update: Now no Parker and no Mills, it is Sheldrick time earlier than expected? It's still a gutsy call to start with him, but Round 0 will tell the story.
Short: Contested bull got his change mid-season and showed he's going to be a Fantasy stud of the future with an insane PPM, the question is if he gets midfield minutes this season
In and out of the side and a gun at lower levels but scoring will always be limited in his small forward role at the top level
A nice intercept defender when on, but scoring typical for a key defender

Comment: A classy, tall midfielder who was touted as a top 10 pick in 2021, but slipped to 21. He didn't play at AFL level in his first season, however played every game he was healthy for in 2023 in a sign of how highly Freo rate him. He was sub or subbed out on seven occasions, and even the games wasn't he only went over 70% TOG six times. So there is clear upside considering his 57 average game from 57% TOG. He'll eventually be an inside midfielder for Freo and from what he's shown he might be a pretty good one, but with Brayshaw, Serong and Young locked into the inside roles, it's hard to see Johnson increasing the 21% CBA figure he averaged last season, so I doubt we'll see the 30+ point bump we need from him to be a viable starting pick at that price and position. Update: Strong reports coming out of Freo on his development, I still find it hard to see him getting the CBA bump given the tight rotation, but he's got himself onto the watchlist.
Short: Looked good in his first season at the level and outside of his seven games where he was sub/subbed off he averaged 75, hard with Serong, Brayshaw and Young being a tight rotation but if he gets consistent inside time, a breakout is on the cards

Comment: The former number three pick has always been on the radar due to his draft position, but is yet to deliver constantly at AFL level. His numbers at VFL level are getting better, averaging 75 in 2021, 97 in 2022 and then an impressive 111 in last season. He just hasn't had a proper crack at it at AFL level due to the midfield depth at Carlton. He played two matches in 2022 and 10 last year, but was sub for five of them. His PPM rate was pretty good, and he averaged 80 when playing the full game. He's now at the Saints who have been trying to inject speed into their midfield for a few seasons now and I can see him getting regular minutes in there this season. Priced at 57 and MID-only, I think you'd want him averaging over 85, which he can do if the CBAs are over 50%. A pre-season watch, not for the first time, but he might have been worth the wait. Update: A pre-season knee injury may stall his Round 1 hopes.
Short: We've been waiting for a breakout and maybe a move to the Saints will unlock that
Hard running wing who might see more than the 10 games he played in 2023, but not a scorer
Defender picked up in the mid-season draft, averaged 76 in the VFL and won the VFL B&F, one to watch
Role player who has been great for Geelong after being picked up in the Rookie Draft, but not one for Fantasy
Talented forward who played 22 games after moving to Geelong, but scoring won't change much in this role
One of the best defenders in the comp and at just 24, he'll improve his reputation again in 2024, however he still won't be Fantasy relevant

Comment: The 22-year-old deserves some luck after two ACL injuries in two seasons. He's played as a small defender which hasn't been conducive to decent Fantasy scoring, but he's also played as a rebounding half-back, and it's the latter that he's said to be earmarked for under Hardwick in 2024. This sparks some interest in him, but the early bye makes it tough. One to keep on the radar in case he does have a Jayden Short type role early in the ear. 23 Feb Update: No Powell but he did appear to be the main distributor in the first of the pre-season matches. We'll get a free look in Round 0, but he's firmly on the radar now.
Short: Coming off successive knee reconstructions he comes in cheap, has scored okay in the past and flagged to play more of a distributor role in 2024
After an interrupted start to his career, he's had a clean bill of health since moving to the Lions, however scoring hasn't changed in that time and nothing to say it will
An ACL injury will see him miss at least the first half of the season for the Lions
Moved back to the wing in 2023 where he's scored 70+ before, but was limited to around the 60 mark and that might be him from here
34-year-old key forward, not the combo you want
Now 30 and always seems to be on the fringe at the Swans
Picked back up in the mid-season draft as a running wing, didn't score well in his years at the Pies and nothing changed at the Dogs

Comment: The former top five pick moved to the Roos in the off-season in search for more opportunity, after averaging 11 games per season. He scored 101 in Round 1 last year, but failed to reach 80 until the Round 24. He did score well at VFL level though, averaging 110. He should be locked into a wing role at the Roos, but it's a role that lacks consistent scoring at AFL level, so I'd keep expectations in check.
Short: A new team should help the former Pick 5 get more chances and scoring at VFL level is good (110), but likely to take a wing role at the Roos which will cap his output

Comment: Cunningham has a booming kick and after a 27% KI rate in the last five games of 2021, I thought he could take his game to the next level after Jordan Dawson left. However, Blakey ended up taking that slack and Cunningham hasn't taken a kick-in since. He played every game last season but was a mix between forward and back. I still have some hope he will improve his output, but not enough to be relevant.
Short: Played every game last year after being on the outer the year before, I was actually bullish on him, but 0% KI the last two seasons shows he's more of a role player than a distributor
Back at the Hawks but I doubt he will return to his scoring when he was there
Small forward who is now at the Dees, however role and scoring will unlikely change
Small forward took a while to find his feet at Port, but even his 63 L5 average isn't nearly enough

Comment: Chapman has showed great signs in his first few seasons at AFL and certainly looks like one for the future. He was limited to just the three matches last year due to a shoulder injury which means he starts at a discounted price, and he's back fit and there's a bit of buzz coming out of Freo about him. He was always behind Young, Ryan and Clark for distribution in defence, but with Young moving to the midfield, he's moves up one spot on the pecking order. The other talk is that he will fill the wing role left by Henry, but it now seems Sharp will take that which is a good thing for Chapman's scoring. I wouldn't even be surprised if we see him spend some time inside. Regardless, he's easily beat his priced at figure, with lower estimates being 75+. Priced at 55, you probably want him averaging over 80 to be a knockout pick, and I think he's certainly capable of that. 10 Feb Update: Sent for scans after injuring his hamstring in the intra-club. It's his hamstrings that he's had issues with in the past. He had hamstring surgery last season and saw a specialist in Spain in the off-season, so it's a bit more concerning that a regular one. Unless news comes out that it's minor, it's time to find a replacement.
Short: Very impressive on limited exposure and heading into his 4th season, was poised to breakout but a pre-season hamstring injury is a big worry given his history
A gun intercept defender but you don't get extra Fantasy points for intercepting
Had his best season yet as Buddy bowed out, but key forward scoring will always be limited
Became a regular last season and looks the goods, but limited to a forward role, not the defensive role he put up monster scores in the VFL
General defender with limited scoring
I thought we'd see more of him after a super impressive debut in 2022, but only played the 10 games for a rebuilding team so not a great sign
Shutdown small defender who was very highly rated prior to breaking a leg but found himself on the outer last season, regardless his scoring in that role will be limited

Comment: Fyfe has been impacted by injuries in six of his last seven seasons, however he's hit rock bottom the last two. He's never been a natural Fantasy player as he's very much in the Dustin Martin mould of too good in real life to worry about tackling or picking up cheap marks. Despite winning two Brownlows and being one of the premier midfielders in the AFL, Fyfe's best Fantasy season average is just 105. He finished 2023 with an average of 49, which is 56 points off his best ever 105. The form drop is both injury related (4 games under 60% TOG in 2024) but also came about from the emergence of the young Freo midfield, meaning Fyfe has been playing more time forward. This time last season, Fyfe was earmarked for a full-time forward role, but that was changed after he struggled in the early rounds and he increased his CBAs as the season went on, before a season ending injury in Round 16. He's back training with the mids this season and while he's going to be behind Serong, Brayshaw and Young for CBA rotations, I see him staying at the 40% mark. I think he can push his scoring up to the 75-80 mark, which actually makes him an okay starting option, particularly if he can get a few 90+ scores early. However, his body, role and output has been too hard to trust in recent years, so there is a lot of risk in the pick. 27 Feb Update: 20 touches in a half of match-sim. There wasn't much opposition and little counting stats (only 40 AF from 20 touches), but he won it contested in a full-time mid role. He looked too good to pass up in a year lacking top end forwards, I think he'll play a nice role.
Short: Six years of injury impacted seasons, but looking fit and spending more time in the middle, I don't mind him
A nice intercept marker, but a genuine full-back and not a player you want in your team
Mature age forward looked great in his two matches at AFL level last year and set for a regular role with the departure of Shultz, but the role is a small pressure forward so scoring will be limited
Was a regular 80+ scorer at the GC, but in the general forward role at the Blues he's been closer to the 60s and it's hard to see that changing without a role change
Key defender who got a bump in 2022 with McGovern out, averaging 80 post-bye, but likely back to the 60s now
Small forward who regressed from his AA season of 71, as the Cats did, and might continue to find it tough while Cats aren't as strong
Key forward scoring isn't great, but he'll unfortunately miss the season with an ACL anyway
Plays as a speedy small forward and certainly hasn't looked a scorer to date, spent some time in the midfield in H2 and training there over the pre-season but I doubt that will change things
Fell out of favour but hasn't shown much scoring even with CBAs
Managed just five matches last season and I think GWS might have moved passed him now

Comment: Not sure there’s a harder player to get a read on than Jaidyn Stephenson, in real life and in Fantasy. He burst back into relevance in his first season at the Roos, which included going over 120 twice and 150 once while playing as a CBA midfielder. He then took a step back in 2022, but finished the season in the backline and while he was found out at times defensively, he provided some run and looked at his best, averaging 86 points in his last five with 28% kick-ins. However, Clarko put him back to the forward-line last season and he managed the lowest average of his career. It sounds like Fisher and McKercher are going to take the half-back roles, and there is no room in the midfield now, so I imagine Stephenson will be used as a forward or wing in 2024, and while it's hard to see him not improving on 2023, I doubt it's going to be anything significant.
Short: As hard to read as any in the game, has had stretches where can could be a top 6, either in defence or inside mid, but played mostly forward under Clarko and that's going to limit his scoring

Comment: Zak Jones has progressed from a half-back flanker to a wingman to an inside midfielder, where he provided something different to the plethora of inside mids (Steele, Ross, Brad Crouch). He played the role pretty well in 2021, averaging 89 highlighted by a 151 and 123 in consecutive weeks. He hasn't hit those heights since though, averaging 65 and 55 from 13 and four games due to an Achilles issue and then a quad strain, after dealing with soft tissue issues in 2022. He played his first game in the VFL in Round 14 and then scored 127 in his second VFL game. That saw him back in the 1s for the first time under Ross, and in the three full games he averaged 48% CBAs which is a great sign. However, an early knee injury finished his season in Round 20. He enters 2024 still less than 30 and priced at 54. He can surpass that by 25 points if he maintains that midfield role. There hasn't been much said of him this pre-season, but he's one I'm keeping an eye on.
Short: Two interrupted seasons after back-to-back 89s, if he can get back to full fitness and play a midfield role, he could prove a sleeper in 2024
Vandermeer has some talent, but scoring hasn't moved much from the 50-mark
Irishman showed some great signs with a booming kick and became a regular with 19 games in 2023, but doesn't look like he's going to be a scorer
Key defender who's career best was when he took 60% of the KIs, that won't happen again so he'll remain around the 50-mark

Comment: Thilthorpe has been a slow burn since being taken with Pick 2 of the 2020 draft. It was always going to be the case being a tall forward, but he's slowing increased his ruck time while giving ROB a chop out. There is talk that he might take over as the number one option in 2024, which would be a big call as while no star, ROB has been serviceable. But if it occurs, we might see a nice 20+ point bump to his scoring. I doubt it will be enough to be a worthwhile selection, but let's see how he goes in the pre-season matches.
Short: Been a slow burn but word is he might progress to the number one ruck this season, which would bring about a nice boost in scoring

Comment: Tsatas arrived at the Bombers with high hopes following over 33 disposals and seven marks a game throughout his NAB League campaign. A pre-season injury meant he wasn't available to start the season and then was forced to work hard for his spot, despite the Bombers' woes. He played seven VFL matches and had more than 30 touches in two of them. He came in for the final four games of the year and looked okay without being amazing, limited to a forward and wing role with little inside action (15% CBAs). Natural development and a full pre-season should set him up for a second-year breakout, but the Bombers have so many who can run through the inside and I have Hobbs and Caldwell over him in the rotation, so we might see him having to bide his time in lesser roles. A watch for the pre-season given his forward status and ball winning ability, but I haven't got great hopes for him this season.
Short: A meniscus tear last pre-season saw the highly touted topfive draftee have to wait until Round 21 for a debut and VFL and NAB League form suggest he'll be a scorer
Club change but still a key defender so scoring will unlikely change
Plays the defensive forward role super well for the Pies, just not a role for Fantasy
Lockdown defender who looked at home in the AFL in his first season, not a scorer though
Ferocious key forward who applied a lot of pressure, now a regular for Freo but hard to see his scoring become relevant in this game
Changed club but won't be in a scoring role nor has he shown scoring ability

Comment: The 2022 draft is looking like a special one and the player taken at Pick 10 could end up as good as any. Phillipou has all the attributes of a modern-day player - a big body, high leap, booming kick and a goal kicker. The only thing he didn't demonstrate in his debut season was accumulation, but he showcased that in his draft year where he averaged 123 from eight games. He played a deep forward role in his first season, but got a taste of the midfield as the season went on - 5% CBAs pre-bye, 13% post and 20% in the L5. It's inevitable he ends up as a midfielder, but with no shortage of midfielders at the Saints at the moment, I doubt we'll see a significant jump this year.
Short: Massive numbers in his draft year and comparisons to Bont and Danger, played a deep forward role to start his career but a bump in CBAs to finish the season might be a sign of things to come
Shutdown defender who did his ACL last season and will miss a fair bit of 2024
Key utility who actually really impressed as a forward in 2023, but neither role is good for scoring
Just the seven matches last season with strangely three as sub proves he's there for ruck depth
A trade to the Hawks after just 1.5 seasons at the Dons, beautiful user and could play on a wing this season but I'm not sure he's much of an accumulator

Comment: Top 10 pick with monster junior numbers (109 average in WAFL Colts, three x 130+ in WAFL league), high endurance and good size. After just four games in his debut season (2 as sub), Erasmus played 14 matches last season. However, six of those he wore the vest, so he finished with 52 average from 51% TOG. His numbers at the lower level and PPM at AFL in his second season suggest he might be a scorer of the future. I think we'll see a lot more of him this season following the departures in the off-season, but it's still going to be hard to get consistent CBAs with Brayshaw, Serong, Young, Johnson, Fyfe and O'Meara taking up the majority. Expect a nice bump in average, but it might be a year or two before we see him putting up consistent numbers worthy of Fantasy selection.
Short: Former top 10 pick got his chance last year but was used sparingly with six vests, but he's an accumulator at the lower level and should see more TOG this season following the departures

Comment: After nine games in three seasons, West finally got his chance in 2022 and carved out a nice role as a small pressure forward. However, that didn't last long, and he was back out of the side for most of the first half of 2023. West was a highly touted inside midfielder as a junior, but with the depth of the midfield at the Dogs, he looks like he's going to continue in the forward role when in the side. While that's the case, he won't be a factor in Fantasy.
Short: I though he found a spot as a small forward in 2022, but he continued to be in and out if the side in 2023 and I doubt we'll see him in a midfield role which is where he'd need to be to score
Emerging key forward who showed off his strong set of hands in his first season of playing AFL, has future star all over him but unlikely to be a Fantasy one

Comment: A back up ruck to Draper who has impressed at reserves level. He won the VFL Best and Fairest for the Bombers in 2021 and increased his VFL average from 87 to 116 last season, showing his potential. Draper has been the clear choice for number one ruck at Essendon, but he's had an interrupted pre-season so hopefully we see more of Bryan this year.
Short: Been third in line behind Draper and Phillips but VFL numbers are impressive, so he hopefully gets his chance now Phillips has gone and Draper has been interrupted
Missed all of 2023 with a serious hamstring injury and now 32, he's not a great option in this game
Small forward who is a nice addition to West Coast's list, but in that role his scoring is going to be limited
Key defender who excels in one-on-ones but is surrounded by better ball users so won't get much possession

Comment: The big Humper is a fun watch. Hits the ball hard, skilful and gets the ball in the right spots. He's in the De Goey, Petracca, Dusty mould of a very dangerous forward of centre player. It's the role every football team wants but it's a very hard role to play, and when it comes to Fantasy, typically these players are better IRL than their Fantasy scores suggest. I think he'll continue to develop his fitness and craft in a 20/80 fwd/mid split, but he's only an injury or two away from that flipping the other way and he could be a factor in Fantasy this season, but I'm keeping my expectations in check for the future star.
Short: Pick six of 2022 really impressed in his first season as a powerful fwd/mid which is a hard role to play but he's going to end up a very good one

Comment: There's no doubting Coleman-Jones has talent, however he's yet to really crack it at AFL level. Not even a move to the Kangaroos provided more job security, with just 19 games since arriving in 2022 at an average of 52. He continued to dominate at lower level, highlighted by a 167 in R8 last year after averaging 104 and 115 at VFL level the two years prior. Those scores came from playing predominantly in the ruck and at AFL level, he plays as a key forward. If he's ever handed to keys to be the number one ruck then he could be worth a look, but that's an unlikely scenario. Maybe if Xerri goes down, which we certainly don't want!
Short: Yet to cement his spot even with the move to North, but Goldy out should open up some R2 opportunities
Just the five games last season (2 as sub) after seven in his debut season, SANFL average of 81 is encouraging and might get a chance with Duursma traded

Comment: Bonner has had flashes of good scores throughout his career, however he's never put together a full season. He should get more chances this season after a move to Saints in the off-season, but MID-only rules him out.
Short: Now at the Saints after showing flashes at Port, MID-only makes it hard but 104 SANFL average shows he can score if given a chance
Fringe player and hasn't scored well since 2019 when he was in a wing role
Gun intercept defender better in real life than Fantasy
Will only continue to grow in his role with Buddy now gone but won't score enough to be relevant

Comment: Schoenberg had slowly increased his midfield role, from 18% CBAs in 2020, 35% in 2021, 38% in the first half of 2022 and then 56% to finish. However, that dropped to 30% in 2023 as he found himself out of the Crows' best 22, playing 11 matches and sub for 3. Adelaide have drafted very well in recent times and the acquisitions of Pedler, Rachelle, Soligo and Rankine have provided a different dimension to the Crows, and with Dawson and Laird taking full-time midfield roles, 105 SANFL average is encouraging though, however he'll be spending the start of the season recovering from a ruptured Achilles.
Short: Recovering from a ruptured Achilles, however fell out of favour in 2023 with Soligo/Rachelle/Pedler/Rankine taking priority
Key position player who has struggled for games at multiple clubs, now a premiership player but I doubt his scoring will change
Medium forward who was trialled in defence in 2023, not sure what Dimma has planned for him but I doubt it will result in a bump in scoring
Natural half-forward which Adelaide seem to have a lot of so he played in defence in 2023, SANFL average was okay without catching the eye
Small pressure forward who has been a regular the past two seasons but scoring is limited
Another club change but scoring hasn't been great in any role
Hard working half-forward but a role player for the Dons and might find opportunities limited again this season
Back playing most weeks after being in and out of the side in 2022, but playing in a far more defensive role than he did when he averaged 86
Played 18 matches after being overlooked in the draft and showed plenty, but a 20-year-old key forward so won't be relevant in this game

Comment: After seeing consistent midfield minutes in his debut season with 31% CBAs in the first half, Jordon took up a wing role in 2022 left vacant by Brayshaw moving to a half-back. He played an important role for the team, playing 22 games at an average of 72. However, the acquisition of Hunter on a wing pushed Jordon out and meant he spent time forward in a bit role, including being sub/subbed off seven times. Remove these sub 51% TOG games and he averaged 67, which is more in line with his first two seasons, however in a lesser role. He showed he's developed as a scorer though, averaging 120 in the VFL. While the Swans' midfield is getting pretty deep, they have lost Stephens on a wing and Mills for the front part of the season. I can see Jordon getting some minutes in the middle and if he does, he's more than capable of a 75+ average and higher if it's inside mid, which as a forward this year makes him a great pick. It's a good and bad thing that he plays Round 1, so we'll have a good look at his role and scoring, but at that price point he's one I'm okay starting with if he can go 75+, despite the Round 5 bye. 27 Feb Update: Parker out only helps his midfield push, even if that means wing. We'll get a full look in Round 0, but the risk is even lower now.
Short: Moved to the Swans after being kicked out of the midfield/wing rotation at the Dees where he showed signs in the last, fresh start with forward status could be just what he (and we!) are after

Impressed in his debut season with some (not me) saying he'll end up better than Ashcroft, but second season as a wing with MID-only status, he's not going to be that for at least this year unless he moves inside
Never been an accumulator of the football, illustrated by his best career season being 60 in 14 seasons
Forward status and new coach could bring a role change, but there's a bit going on there at the moment
Some massive scores in the VFL but played a shutdown role when at AFL level, which he didn't do a heap of in 2023
Small forward, better in real life than in Fantasy, as showed by his impact in the finals series
Fringe defender who has never been an accumulator and unlikely to change
Small forward has showed plenty in his first two seasons, but that still led to a sub-50 average such is the role
Key defender in his 13th season and never been a scorer
Small forward who lost his spot in 2023 and even when he does play, he doesn't make an impact in this game
Defender without much attacking side to his game
Back-to-back injury impacted seasons and that 89 season seems a distant memory

Comment: The former pick 28 played seven games in his debut season and impressed with his kicking skills and speed. However, he only managed the three games at AFL level last season with Taranto and Hopper taking the midfield spots. In a developing side under a new coach, I expect to see a lot more of Sonsie in 2024 and while I doubt he'll have a big impact, he's worth monitoring with his forward status. 115 and 117 in back-to-back weeks at VFL level before suspension finished his season shows he does have the potential to score.
Short: Impressed in his debut season but the arrival of Taranto and Hopper meant he played just the three last season, highly touted and I think we'll see a lot more of him in 2024 will need time before being a regular midfielder
Former Pick 8 has had a disappointing career to date and fell out of favour last season managing just 12 games after 18+ the three prior, scoring has been limited throughout also
33-year-old small forward who scored well in the past with stints in the midfield, but those days are over now
Gun small defender, often takes the opposition's number one medium forward, not a role for producing decent scores
Solid defender but best season average is just 59
Mid-season pickup with some nice forward craft, West Coast might have found one here but a young key forward won't score much in this game
Has shown signs he'll be a gun IRL one day with his size and elite marking ability, but will need a few years before he's mature enough to make an impact in Fantasy
Club change worked great for him in 2023 but the dashing defender has never been much of a scorer

Comment: Williams has been disappointing since his move to the Blues - for Carlton fans and Fantasy coaches. He was a popular mid-priced pick in 2021 following a change of clubs for more midfield time after averaging 106 in the second half of 2019 in a midfield role. After a string of poor performances, he was banished from the midfield and played in defence. That defence role continued before he badly injured his calf, missing the majority of the season. He then did his ACL in the 2023 pre-season and missed the entire year. He now enters 2024 priced at 49 which is about 30 less than what he can produce in a defensive role and 40 less in a midfield role. Regardless of role, he's significantly underpriced and one of the bargains of the season. The only issue is his Round 2 bye. How much will he have to score in Round 0 for you to pick him? I think 75+ will make it worthwhile, which I expect him to do.
Short: Due for a change of luck and as long as he's healthy, he'll prove one of the bargains of the season
Played 17 matches in his second season and showed clear talent with his intercept marking ability, will get better again but role isn't conducive to decent scoring
Moving to Richmond should see him become a regular in 2023, but key forward scoring won't change much
The veteran medium forward has been on the fringe of the Demons' 22 for a while now and when he does play it's as a role player

Comment: The Pick 7 of the 2022 National drat was one of the most hyped rookies leading into last season after he scored 92 in the pre-season match, second highest for the Hawks, from a juicy midfield role. And after 80 from 52% CBAs in R1, it look like he was going to be one of the rookies for the season. However, never went above 30% after that, and despite a 94 in R3, he quickly found himself out of the Hawks' best 22, playing as sub in R5 and dropped after R6. He then played as sub a further three times and played twice in the last eight rounds. His VFL numbers were encouraging in that time, averaging 93 for the season but had two scores 119+. He enters 2024 with forward status and with another pre-season under his belt, will be eying off a spot in the midfield. The issue is, a lot are at the Hawks. But if he happens to be the one to soak up the midfield minutes from Day, who might be missing the start of the season, or Worpel, who I can see missing out, then he might be worth jumping on. Like I've said before with second year breakouts, you can afford to wait a few weeks to see if his role and scoring is sustainable first. 23 Feb Update: CBA role in pre-season. Bumped up slightly, but I still view him the same.
Short: Solid debut season but after 92 in the pre-season match, I think we expected more, forward status makes him of interest in his second season though if he can recapture that form and role
22 games in 2023 as a small forward/wing, averaged sub-50 in his career to date and unless there's a role change, it's hard to see that changing

Recruited as a mature age running defender to fill the void of Heath Shaw retiring and Zac Williams' departure, but GWS have no shortage of those, and he's spent most his time in the VFL or on a wing at AFL level
A tall (193cm) midfielder who has nice numbers in juniors and VFL, but been on the fringe at the Cats and there are a few ahead of him in the midfield mix

Mature-aged defender who arrived with some massive VFL scores and got his chance after 112 and 136 in R2 & R4, but played a more defensive role at AFL level meaning that scoring power didn't carry across - 43 average post-bye
Has put up some big numbers in the VFL, averaging 90+ the last three years, but yet to show it at AFL level
Promising key forward who has showed he'll become a very good player, but young key forwards are never good Fantasy options
Key position defender and will be a star in the future but unfortunately he's better in real life than Fantasy
Talented defender with elite intercept marking ability but plagued by injuries and his body is too hard to trust now
Multiple goals in six games, goalless in every other game (including seven straight!) is too inconsistent to consider
Big ball winner in the WAFL and as a junior but often in the defensive forward role at AFL level which just isn't a scoring option
Defensive-minded inside mid with high handballing numbers, played two matches in his debut season and looked good this pre-season
Interrupted last two seasons, highly rated but tough at that price and MID-only
Former steeplechaser is highly rated at the Lions, but their midfield has so many mouths to feed and it's hard to see Sharp breaking in
Tall, outside mid/winger with big numbers in his draft year and at VFL level, but yet to really show he can accumulate at the top
Returning from an ACL and hopefully we see the best of him as he showed some great signs early, but a young key forward role always see his scoring limited

Mobile ruck/key forward played 14 matches in 2023 after scoring -2 in his sole game beforehand, showed some great signs and will see more chances with Soldo on the move but I doubt he'll score much with Nank healthy
Heartbreakingly missing out on the Prelim and GF with an ankle injury, but a genuine key back and scoring is relatively capped
Big SANFL numbers for a number of years now, but still behind O'Brien and even Thilthorpe who looks next in line for the number one ruck role
Drafted as a mid but found his own in the small forward role at WC and looks like he's going to be a good one, not for Fantasy though
Depth ruck with monster VFL numbers (112 average in 2022, 96 while coming back from injury in 2023) and Ross seemed pretty happy to ruck Marshall solo
Reliable defender but unless he somehow moves into a distribution role, there's little upside in his Fantasy relevance

Comment: Hewett is the modern midfielder who breaks from stoppages and hits the scoreboard. While his numbers don't look great (55 average in his draft year, 46 in his 14 AFL matches and 26 in the WAFL last year), he's a much better player than that. In his draft year, he scored 115 when returning through the WAFL Reserves in 2022 and had a huge game one for WA in the U18 Champs where he picked up BOG honours, collecting 29 disposals and two goals. He then spent most of his year in the WAFL against tougher opposition, which is why his junior scores are lower than the other first rounders of the draft. He showed some great signs in his debut season in a limited role and TOG. He's dealing with a foot issue this pre-season, so I think it's going to be a slow build, but he might be a player of the future.
Short: Showed spark in his debut season and WC now have a few decent kids coming through, will be more forward than mid in the short term but should be a midfielder in time
Good on social media but fell out of the side in Round 5 and is yet to show much scoring ability
On the wrong side of 30 and key forward not a great combo
Debuted in 2023 and played every game as a shutdown defender, excelled in the role however scoring looks very limited

The key forward has had a season where he averaged 86 (which would rank him 8th amongst current forwards), however, he's more the 50-60 player we've seen the last few years when he's managed to stay on the park
One game for the season and SANFL average did improve from 57 in 2022 to 74, but still doesn’t catch the eye
Just three games in two seasons and unlikely to get much ball in the Dogs' backline with their half-back options anyway
Mid-season draftee from 2021 has some very nice forward attributes, but been in and out of the side and forward role isn't great in this game
The club change might help the talented goal-kicker after a slow season in and out of the vest but small forward role won't change
Gun key defender but his best ever season average being 54 indicates he's not a scorer
Is going to be a star key forward, if not already be a gun when he can get some consistency but as a key forward he won't be much of a scorer in this game
Medium defender who has played 16 games since being drafted but average around the 50s and VFL average in the 60s indicates he's not much of a scorer
Limited to a small forward role, which isn't Fantasy-friendly, he may one day progress into the midfield and there are spots open, but I'd need to see it first
Played six full games last season but averaged just 52 as a medium defender and VFL scoring doesn't indicate there will be much of a change
Thrown around in a few key positions but hasn't shown much on the scoring front since juniors
Picked back up in the mid-season draft, hadn't scored great in the past at AFL level and that didn’t really change when he got his second chance
Played one game for 62 but averaging 65 and 68 in juniors and the VFL respectively doesn't read well
Looks great as a small forward, just not a Fantasy scorer

Never managed more than six games in a season since being drafted, but should get his chance this season and there is positive noise coming from Richmond about his pre-season, scoring appears limited at VFL level though
Very consistent… just the wrong type, scoring between 41 and 68 in all 10 of his full games
Strong bodied defender seems a favourite at Port and was even flagged for mid-time in the past, scoring at all levels is underwhelming though
Former Pick 6 played 14 matches in his first season for the Swans, displayed some of his intercept marking ability but not much else from a scoring perspective

Comment: Arrived as a mature age (26) SSP selection after being SANFL's premier key forward in recent years, averaging 128 in 2021. He didn't disappoint, scoring 111 on debut and I had to double take if it was him or Marshall. Unfortunately, he did his knee in Round 6 and missed the rest of the season. He then missed the majority of the 2023 season with a foot injury. Hopefully he gets a proper run at it this season and might eat into Marshall's scoring, but I doubt he's going to be relevant himself.
Short: Back from injury but will likely play back-up to Marshall
Former first rounder scored nicely at SANFL level but stuck as a small forward at AFL level and can't get away from the sub vest
Sharman has an impressive set of hands and played 16 matches last season after a handful the two prior, playing as a 3rd tall which makes it tricky for consistent scoring
Has managed to get his body right after frequent injury concerns earlier in his career, however genuine key defenders don't score well
Tough defender who I confuse with Moore at times such is his marking ability, but far from a scorer in Fantasy
Great VFL average but not a scorer as a medium forward at AFL level
A move to the GC gave hope he could become a consistent scorer of the half-back, but scoring actually dropped from his time as the Saints where he averaged 82 in the L5 of 2022
Mid-season draftee from the SANFL is now a regular at the Dons in a small forward role, not a great role for Fantasy though
Small forward role which limits his scoring
Picked up in the mid-season draft in 2022 but has only managed five games with an average below 60, will likely be a regular in 2024 with North's injuries down back but VFL numbers he's not a scorer
Good scorer at SANFL level but stuck as a small forward in the AFL
A career average below 50 is about expected for the Irishman in his defensive role
Yet to show much scoring even at SANFL level
Elite running capacity which allowed him to shut down some of the best runners in the AFL, but it’s not a role that leads to scoring

Comment: Sweet has played 11 matches in the past three seasons as a back-up ruck to one of the best in the comp. In that time, he's put up some massive scores in the VFL, including 125 in his last six matches of 2023. So when the trade was made which saw him move to Port, a team who lost their ruck (Lycett) last year, we all thought he'd be the perfect R2 for us this season. However, shortly after the move, Port also added Soldo who I think is the better ruck. The setup is still worth monitoring in the pre-season just in case they decide to go with Sweet, but with the other options out there (Gawn, Grundy, Xerri), Sweet has lost a lot of his appeal. Update: With Soldo only returning to training from a finger injury, it sounds like Sweet might start the season as Port's R1. He costs a bit more than an ideal R3, but with Gawn and Grundy having an early bye, I'd be prepared to pay up for Sweet as R3 if he's named solo in Round 1.
Short: Mature-aged ruckman who played back-up at the Dogs so a move to Port in the off-season gave hope until Soldo joined him shortly after, but Soldo pre-season injury could open the door
Crafty medium forward put some good numbers up in the WAFL but stuck forward at AFL level and won't get near the same output
Didn't skip a beat after missing 2022, a very good defender but a pure lockdown who won't score great in this game
Former first rounder has had an interrupted start to his career but had his chance last season and didn't show much, will need time
The Cannon has become a better player now he's more focused on shutdown roles, unfortunately it means his scoring will be limited

Comment: 23 Feb Update: So the half-back role seems legit. Ball use a bit messy but if they persist with him, he's going to outperform that price in a line where we're going to have to pick value players to start anyway. Shades of Constable/Atkins of 2023 so it might be a rocky road, but let’s see how he looks in Round 0.
Short: Been on the outer the past four seasons after being a regular goal kicker for the Suns, word is he's training as a rebounding defender which could bring him into relevance, a watch in the pre-season games
Solid role in defence but it's not a scoring one

Versatile former high pick impressed everyone in his first season, playing 20 games, but limited to just 11 since, still not sure what role he'll play and while he's cheap, he hasn’t shown he's a scorer
Small forward who managed 22 games in 2023 but very limited scoring at all levels
Had a solid season with 17 games but even the 52 he averaged excluding his five sub games isn't what we're after

Been waiting in the wings as a backup ruck and got his chance in 2023 when Witts was injury, faced a baptism of fire going up against Marshall and Darcy/Jackson in his two games, Dimma might change things but Witts will likely continue as solo
Great SANFL numbers and showed he could score with a ton first game back after the nasty concussion in Round 2, probably want some security in his spot first though but he has a nice mark-kick game
Scored his best when rucking, but Port have him to play a key defensive role so his scoring will be similar to last
A consistent defender for the Cats, never surpassed 58 in a season though
Speedy half-back managed two games at AFL level in his debut season and averaged 62 in the VFL, doesn't appear a scorer
Key defender coming back from an ACL injury
Key forward has struggled to cement a spot to date, talk of him switching to defence where I doubt we'll see the scoring bump his brother got from the same move
Has some nice forward craft but just the single score over 60 from 13 games last season

Comment: The former top 10 pick did his ACL in 2022 and then struggled with soft tissue injuries on return, meaning he hasn't played a game for 24 months. However, he has attributes to be a good Fantasy defender, a neat kick and ability to generate marks. He finished 2020 averaging 83 in the last five games and that's about the mark I think he can produce at his best. He's obviously going to need some time to find his feet when he returns but gets a fresh start at the Dogs and is one mid-pricer I'd seriously consider if named in Round 1.
Short: Hasn’t played for 24 months and coming off some shocking injuries, but has always had attributes to be a good Fantasy defender and a move to the Dogs will hopefully unleash that
Well on the outer with just one game in 2023, decent scorer at VFL level but will be stuck forward at AFL level
Fringe key position player with very limited scoring
Genuine role player who even played backup ruck at times in 2023, averaged in the 40-50 range his whole career indicates he's not a scorer
Small forward has improved his output in the state league but even with removing his sub-affected scores his scoring isn't great at AFL level
Rioli breaking out and Short moving back to defence saw the dashing defender regress in 2023, unless Yze really mixes it up, I doubt he makes an impact in 2024
Former first rounder is a nice size and managed 15 matches last season, however scoring was very limited which isn't a surprise considering his VFL averages
Key defender and certainly not a scorer
Found his spot as the lockdown small defender at Freo but recovering from an ACL injury

Comment: Robertson was one of the most hyped rookies in Fantasy when he was drafted, following his elite scoring in his draft year; 113 average in the National Championships (ranked 1) and 120 average in WAFL colts (also ranked 1). He hasn’t done a heap at AFL level in his first four seasons, and despite matching his career high 16 matches in 2023, he bottomed out with a 39 average. This was largely due to his four games as sub and when in the team, he spent a lot of time forward. His 114 in the VFL shows he still has it and improved from 104 the year prior. Dunkley and Ashcroft took his midfield minutes last year but with no Ashcroft, could we see DevRob injected back in the middle? I doubt it but he's always worth tracking due to his elite scoring at the lower level. Underwent surgery after playing in the Lions' Grand Final loss with a broken wrist and has had an interrupted pre-season.
Short: Junior gun who has displayed that same level of ball winning ability in the VFL, but limited to a forward or defensive role when at AFL level where his scoring has been limited, worth tracking if the CBAs ever come
Had some good scoring at VFL level but need some role certainty as his only game in 2023 was in the vest
The son-of does some nice things in defence but only eight games averaging less than 40 in his career to date
Snuck in for the PF and GF but he's on the fringe and has never scored well
Athletic ruck prospect with a booming kick currently playing forward and behind the big boys at the Cats
Talks the highly rated tall may move to defence this season and even seen taking kick-ins at training, but I doubt he'll bump his scoring much
Has averaged well at lower levels but never broken in for a proper go at it
Lockdown defender and not a scorer
Star defender IRL but not a scorer in this game
Developing tall played every game after Round 15 with West Coast's injuries, but scoring is very limited and will need time to develop
Came straight in and played the first six matches as a lockdown defender, only featured one more time for the season and will likely need time to develop
Mature-aged key defender who played 19 matches in his debut season but very much a lockdown back
Struggled to stay on the park but shown potential of being a very good key forward, unlikely to be relevant in this game though
Former first rounder expected to see more opportunities after moving to the Hawks from the Cats, but didn't play a game and scoring at VFL level didn't catch the eye
Pressure forward with a lot of pace, role not one for scoring though
Now at the Suns after struggling for games at the Roos, likely to just be a depth player
Change of clubs should see him play more than his six games in four seasons, but role will be the same which is a lockdown full-back
Showed some nice signs in his 10 games during his debut season, small forward role will keep his scoring limited
Fringe key defender who did improve his VFL average to 82, but scoring will be limited if he gets a chance at AFL level
Hasn't shown the ball-winning capabilities of his brother, with neither his AFL nor VFL average very appealing
Son of Boomer played three matches in his debut season after impressing as a strong marking medium forward in the VFL, scoring limited at both levels though
Developing tall defender who famously finished top 10 in AFL Fantasy Classic in 2021, not relevant himself though
Key forward to managed 13 games in 2023 and could see even more in 2024, but scoring will be limited in the role

Young ruck developing nicely in the VFL and debuted in R24 last year, I think he becomes the Cats' number one ruck this season and while scoring will be limited (74 VFL average), he's an R3 option if Sweet doesn't play
Hard working key forward will miss the entire season with a hip injury
Sounds like he's moving back to defence the season which will give his scoring a boost but not by enough to be relevant
Defender-turned-forward who is in and out of the side, will likely miss a chunk of the season, if not considerably more
Finds himself at a third club after being named at full-back in the 2023 VFL team of the year
Young key forward switched to defence in 2023 and scoring at VFL level was okay, likely to stay limited at AFL level though
Hopefully see more of the former Pick 15 in 2024, scoring at VFL level is very limited though

Comment: Finlay is developing well in the VFL in a very hard team to break into. There was no under-age football in his draft year, so we had to rely on his 2019 year where he played as a 17-year-old for Oakleigh Chargers, a team that boasted Matt Rowell, Noah Anderson and Will Phillips in the midfield. Finlay was forced to play mostly across half-forward but showed some great signs and from all reports was more advanced than his (half) brother who by contrast only came good during the second half of his draft year. We saw the similarities in Finlay's debut when he was thrown into the middle for the final quarter and racked up over 10 disposals. He also managed 47 from just 37% TOG when used in the middle in his one game last season when sub. He’s averaged over 90 in the VFL since drafted, so the talent is there. Priced at 34 and with forward status, I think he’s worth considering if he’s named Round 1 as an expensive rookie but with more experience.
Short: Brother-of who has averaged over 90 in the VFL since being drafted, worth spending the extra cash if he gets his chance
Was recruited as a hard-running midfielder, but been used as a small forward when at AFL level and opportunity and scoring been limited

Comment: Hore returns to the AFL four years after being delisted. He was handy enough at AFL level, including four x 80+ games in the first six rounds of 2019. He's added to his game in the VFL where he's averaged over 100 the past two seasons, compared to the 87 he went at in his initial draft year. Last season's average included seven scores over 120, thanks to a very high kick-to-handball ratio, highlighted by 31 kicks and one handball in his final game of the year. Rivers has been talked to be making a midfield move which could open up a spot for Hore in defence. We'll get a good look in the opening round, but he's one that if named in Round 1, he should be a worthwhile selection despite the early bye.
Short: Second chance at the Dees after being a mature-age draftee previously, averaged 62 back then but VFL form been prolific (over 30 kicks(!) in two of his last five games)
I didn't have the fringe key defender playing on a wing in 2024 on my bingo card, but that's where he's been training, might lead to a boost in scoring but I doubt it will be sustainable
Small forward played 13 games in 2023 and showed great excitement, but role isn't good for scoring
Rebounding defender who caught the eye with 28 intercept possessions in a NAB League match, but scoring was modest in his first season at senior level
24-year-old full-back has cemented himself as the main man in deep defence for the Crows, not a scorer though
Emerging defender played 12 games in 2023, but sub-40 average
A developing ruck who is now further back in the queue with Flynn arriving
Hard to crack a game for the Lions and VFL scoring doesn't catch the eye
Nice draft year numbers but that was as a mid, plays small forward in the VFL and scoring is limited
Versatile tall training as a mobile ruck which would be a boost compared to the tall forward and defender roles of the past
Former Hawk picked up by Geelong in the off-season, scoring at VFL level limited
The original Sun has managed just 13 matches in the last three seasons and likely to be a depth player again
Cat-B key defender likely to be on the fringe again

Comment: 18 Feb Update: Played as a pure mid in the A team during the North intra, the buzz continues, if named R1 he's a perfect cheap forward option.
Short: VFL accumulator yet to show much at the top level yet, but there's some buzz coming out of North on him so worth monitoring over the pre-season games
210cm grew up playing rugby union, improved his VFL average from 32 to 72 last season so he's developing, but Grundy's arrival squashes any chance we see him regularly this season
Hard, contested ball winning midfielder but hasn't cracked it yet in the AFL
Hard team to crack but his name keeps popping up and a young player who will play more in 2024, but role likely to be limited
Decent in the VFL but played a small forward role in his four games in 2023, one to watch as the Dees have some midfield spots to fill

Comment: Sharp has landed at Freo after being delisted by the Suns last season. It was a quick downfall considering he was a highly rated junior and showed great signs in 2021. He averaged 118 in the WAFL under 18s in his draft year and saw plenty of league action that season. It took a while to get his chance at AFL level, but in his second season he played the last nine matches for an average of 79 (excluding his sub game). Despite this, he was in and out of the side in 2022, never playing more than four games in a row. But in that time, he averaged 112 in the VFL. He didn't play a single AFL game in 2023, and while his VFL average was lower than 2022, he still managed two x 140+ games. Freo picked him up as a SSP and he's been dominating their running all pre-season. There are some flaws in his game so his job security will always be shaky, but there's a wing spot available and if named in Round 1, he should prove a worthy selection.
Short: Elite runner with a second chance at Freo where he could take Henry's wing spot, averaged over 100 at VFL level since being drafted and priced at 31, can prove great value
A ruck project now further back with Port's acquisition of Soldo and Sweet
Debuted in 2023 after averaging 90 in the WAFL since being drafted, looked a fair way off the pace but his WAFL numbers suggest he can find the footy and worth considering if named
Kept putting huge numbers up in the VFL and should be able to score well when he breaks free of the vest and becomes more of a regular
Depth ruckman picked up a few years ago in the mid-season draft
Picked in the mid-season draft and then traded to Brisbane in the same year, Brisbane already possess one of the top forward-lines so hard to see him getting in
Irishman has struggled for games and scoring at all levels been limited
Former Pick 6 will want to have a big season after just seven matches in 2023, still developing as a key defender and scoring at all levels been limited
Young lockdown key defender has some talent but won't be a scorer
Decent WAFL scorer but no consistency in the AFL side, despite West Coast's struggles
Always gathered nice numbers at VFL level, a second chance at the Pies but you imagine he's there for depth
Another club change and priced 42 below his career best season, keep an eye out in the pre-season but if anything will be in a small forward role where scoring is limited
Brilliant pressure forward but role will always limit his scoring
Back up ruck/forward traded to the Dees, bad hamstring injury in early Feb will limit his pre-season
High leaping, strong marking, medium forward but low VFL numbers indicates he needs more development
KPP who has some talent but yet to show he can score at any level
Former Pick 15 but scoring at all levels has been very limited

Comment: Port Adelaide worked hard to secure the rebounding defender, trading up first during the trade period before trading up on draft day. He backed this up by playing early, debuting in Round 2, however his debut season was hampered by a groin injury and didn't add to his one game. He featured three times in his second season. but sub for two of them and then hamstring surgery finished his season early. If he's named Round 1, defender rookies are scarce, and he comes with good credentials so he's worth watching.
Short: Former Pick 12 sounded like he was going to play early but groin issues halted his first season and a bad hamstring his second, highly rated so hopefully he gets a good run at it this season

Wore the vest in three of his six games in 2023, medium forward role but scoring at VFL level was good enough and he's creating a bit of buzz this pre-season out of the Lions, worth considering if named
Promising tall defender who was taken at Pick 9 in 2021, missed the entire 2023 season with injury and will hopefully bounce back, scoring will likely be limited though

Former top 10 pick where some thought he was as talented as any, has taken a lot of time to develop and had some injury issues, hopefully gets a nice run at it this season but developing key back his scoring will be limited
Put up an impressive 84 in the only game he wasn't sub/subbed but hard to pick without assurances over role and JS
Should improve his overall if he manages to escape the vest but averages in full games were still sub-50
Small forward picked up in last year's mid-season draft, 33 average in his four games
Great scorer as a junior and through the VFL, while the talk of a half-back role is also very enticing, certainly one to consider if named
Didn't shock me that Chris Scott gave the Irishman six matches in his first season coming from Gaelic, meant to be a prodigy in Ireland so will keep on radar but not for a few years yet
I liked the look of the running defender early in his career, but max average of 40 doesn't read well

Pick 16 as an inside mid who saw seven games with midfield exposure last season, which shows the Giants rate him, but it's a hard midfield to crack so I think it will be a while before we see him regularly
Key defender with a very modest scoring history at all levels

Comment: Drawing strong comparisons to Joel Selwood in his draft year, Clark is a strong inside mid with clean disposal and widely valued leadership traits. He was the second highest averaging player during the U18 Champs, going at 105 points per game and earning himself the Vic Country MVP. he also averaged 119 in his last four NAB league games of the season. So when he made his debut as sub in Round 9, it was highly anticipated. He didn't disappoint, laying five tackles and getting six touches in just over a quarter. However, a foot injury forced him to miss the rest of the season. Cats need to inject some youth in there, so we should see a lot more of him in 2024, hopefully without the sub vest on.
Short: Pick eight from 2022 draft didn't play after his debut (where he had five tackles in 25% TOG coming on as sub) due to a foot issue, he's healthy now and Cats need to inject some youth in there, so we should see a lot more of him in 2024
Irishman who has speed but modest scoring at VFL and AFL level
Former Pick 1 who like all young KPP looked a bit lost in year 1, but by all reports had a great pre-season and I think we'll see him in their Best 22 - keep expectations low for now though
Debuted in 2023 and showed some nice defensive attributes despite low scoring
Genuine lock-down key defender, ACL in the pre-season will see him miss the season, does that mean Sicily needs to be more accountable?
202cm ruck is behind the two others at the Hawks, so I doubt we'll see him this season
KPP taken in the mid-season draft in 2022, didn't feature at AFL level in 2023 and might struggle again
Depth ruck at the Blues, in with slightly more of a chance with Silvagni going down with an ACL but he's behind the main two
Yet to play a game, VFL average limited
Lockdown defender with some senior experience but averaged 47 in VFL last year (37 the year before), so he's certainly not a scorer
Small forward and yet to score at AFL level, though he did do nicely at VFL level
Athletic KPP who has elite speed for his size but is still very raw

Comment: Dowling turned out a monster year in the SANFL U18s, filling the stat sheet with nearly 31 disposals, seven marks and five tackles a game on top of kicking 18.15 in front of goal. His standout performance and easily the standout performance of the draft, was his R16 match where he amassed 44 disposals including 35 kicks, to go with 17 marks, six tackles and 4.3 culminating in a 215-point display. He didn't play a game last season, however he showed his scoring capability in the SANFL with three games 108+. They now have a lot of players in his type (fwd/mids), so he might have to wait his time. But if he ever gets his chance, keep an eye on him.
Short: Massive accumulator in his draft year - the highest Fantasy averaging player in the draft which included a 215 game - played a forward role at SANFL level where he scored okay (3 x 108+ scores) but appears to be down the pecking order
Small forward who got exposure in his first season with four games, but might find it hard this season as the Roos have more depth
Had a decent VFL season and could be an option if he plays
Once touted as a top 10 pick in 2022 but and ACL injury in the NAB League saw him slide and miss 2023, but healthy now so it's exciting to see what he can produce
Mature age cat-B rookie, VFL average limited
Drafted as a winger who has great running capacity, but scoring at VFL level suggests he's got a way to go
High-pressure forward who had some decent scores at junior level but in that role, he'll be restricted even if he gets his chance
Mature aged key defender who has battled injury since being drafted, will need time
Versatile tall who has always scored well at the lower level but been a depth player at AFL, and that's unlikely to change now he's at the Crows
Ruck development prospect picked up in the mid-season draft
Predominantly a midfielder but played in defence in the WAFL and scored well enough
Developing ruck with some nice VFL scores, will need time before he makes an impact at AFL level
Very quick but 38 at WAFL level last season
A small-medium running defender and Swans have plenty of them, 42 VFL average not positive
Was a common vest candidate in 2023 and will be only be harder to break in with the acquisition of Adams
Highly rated at GWS however knee injury ruled him out for the season, may take some time but all reports are that he's a good one
Cat-B rookie with a sub-40 VFL average
Tall mid who went first round in 2022 but couldn't crack into a very strong team, all reports are that he's going to be a good one so worth monitoring if he ever gets his chance
Picked up in the mid-season draft and showed a bit on the wing in his two games with the vest, there are a few who are vying for that spot and his scoring at lower level is modest
